ces ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|COVID-19 pandemic in New York City}}\n\n* [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-main.page Coronavirus advice and guidance]\n* [https://www.schools.nyc.gov/school-life/health-and-wellness/coronavirus-update NYC Department of Education]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|New York City|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York City]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|New York City]]\n[[Category:2020 in New York City]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New York City]]\n[[Category:Healthcare in New York City]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|effects of the pandemic in the state|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in New York City}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 COVID-19 pandemic in New York City\n| width           = \n| image           = File:USNS Comfort passing by Statue of Liberty, March 30, 2020.png\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = The {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} passing by the [[Statue of Liberty]] in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak New York CSA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents in the greater New York City area\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[New York City]]\n| first_case      = [[Manhattan]]\n| arrival_date    = mid-February<ref name=EuropeanOrigin>{{cite news|title=Most New York Coronavirus Cases Came From Europe, Genomes Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/science/new-york-coronavirus-cases-europe-genomes.html|last=Zimmer|first=Carl|publisher=New York Times|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref><br/>{{small|(first case found March 1)}}<ref name=March1/>\n| date            = \n| confirmed_cases = {{Unbulleted list\n  |198,988 ([[New York metropolitan area#Combined statistical area|CSA]]; Apr 8)<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Cases US |url=https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |website=www.arcgis.com |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326155740/https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n  |111,424 (NYC; Apr 15)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|title=COVID-19: Data - NYC Health|website=nyc.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401235417/https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|archive-date=April 1, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 29,741 (Apr 15)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\" />\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 7,905-11,083 (Apr 15)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_pdf\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/imm/covid-19-daily-data-summary-04142020-1.pdf|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) - Daily Summary|url-status=live|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.nyc.gov/coronavirus}}\n}}\n\nThe first [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was confirmed in [[New York City]] in March 2020 in a woman who had recently traveled from [[Iran]], a country seriously affected by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] at the time. Nearly a month later, the [[New York metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] was the worst-affected part of the [[United States]], with its medical infrastructure overtaxed.<ref name=\"nyti_Coro\">{{Cite news|last1=Goldstein|first1=Joseph|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Manhattan Woman Is First Confirmed Case in State|work=The New York Times|date=March 1, 2020|page=A24|access-date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302012003/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"npr._NewY\">{{cite web| title = New York City, U.S. Epicenter, Braces For Peak| author = | work = NPR| date = March 24, 2020| access-date = March 26, 2020| url = https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200326185342/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-date = March 26, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|13|df=us}}, the city has more confirmed coronavirus cases than [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in China (disambiguation)|China]], where the epidemic began; [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|the United Kingdom]]; and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/new-york-city-now-has-more-covid-19-cases-than-china-uk/articleshow/75116681.cms|title=New York City now has more COVID-19 cases than China, UK|date=April 13, 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> The encompassing [[state of New York]] has more cases than any foreign country worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-state-more-coronavirus-cases-than-any-country-worldwide-2020-4|title=New York state now has more confirmed coronavirus cases than any country in the world|first=John|last=Haltiwanger|website=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n=== March ===\nAlthough the first case of [[COVID-19]] was confirmed in [[New York State]] on March 1, 2020, its likely the virus was present in New York during mid-February, weeks prior to the first confirmed cases and that the origin of the virus was Europe instead of Asia.<ref>Zimmer, Carl. (8 April 2020). \"Most New York Coronavirus Cases Came From Europe, Genomes Show\". [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/science/new-york-coronavirus-cases-europe-genomes.html New York Times website] Retrieved 13 April 2020.</ref><ref name=March1>{{Cite news|last=West|first=Melanie Grayce|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692 |title=First Case of Coronavirus Confirmed in New York State|date=March 2, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 9, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303050256/https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692 |archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The 39-year-old [[health care worker]], a resident of [[Manhattan]], had returned from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]] on February 25.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York's first case of coronavirus is a health care worker, and officials say more cases are 'inevitable' |first=Holly |last=Yan |first2=Kristina |last2=Sgueglia |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |newspaper=CNN |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200304002946/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n[[File:Interim MTA NYCT President Sarah Feinberg's First Day (49639838632).jpg|thumb|[[New York City Subway]] passengers on March 9, when there were 16 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New York City.]]\nOn March 9, Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] announced that there were 16 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/03/09/new-york-city-coronavirus-case-numbers-health-update|title=Mayor: 16 Coronavirus Cases Confirmed in City|website=ny1.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> By March 25, over 17,800 cases had been confirmed in New York City, and 199 deaths.<ref name=\"nyti_DeBl\">{{cite news| title = De Blasio Calls Stimulus Deal's Treatment of N.Y.C. 'Immoral'| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 25, 2020| access-date = March 25, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325112712/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-date = March 25, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref> NYC's [[infection rate]] was 5 times higher than the rest of the country and were one-third of total confirmed US cases.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perlstein|first=Mike |url=https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d |title=New Orleans is second only to Seattle in COVID-19 cases per capita|date=March 16, 2020|newspaper=4WWL|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192439/https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d |archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The reasons for this continue to be discussed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/03/coronavirus-new-york-coronavirus-hit-nyc-hard-12504210/ |title=Coronavirus New York: Why has coronavirus hit NYC so hard? |date=April 3, 2020 |publisher=Metro}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, infection in New York City surpassed 23,000, with 365 deaths including a nurse in Manhattan and a civilian staff member in the [[New York City Police Department]] (NYPD). [[Queens]] was the worst effected borough accounting for 34% of deaths, followed by [[Brooklyn]] and [[the Bronx]] at 22%, Manhattan at 15% and [[Staten Island]] at 7%. The majority of those who died had underlying health issues.<ref name=\"nyti_N.Y.\">{{cite news| title = N.Y.C. Death Toll Hits 365 as Case Count Tops 23,000| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 27, 2020| access-date = March 28, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200328045217/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html| archive-date = March 28, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref> Between March 28 and 29, the number of deaths in New York City tripled from the previous 24-hour period; 222 people died of the virus bringing the city's fatalities to 672, with 30,765 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Jen Chung |title=Coronavirus Updates: 222 COVID-19 Deaths Reported In NYC Over 24 Hours |url=https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |work=Gothamist |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329145514/https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 29, [[CBS News]] reporter [[Maria Mercader]], a New York City resident, died from a COVID-19 related illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/ |title=Remembering CBS News journalist Maria Mercader|accessdate=March 31, 2020|via=www.cbsnews.com|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330235009/https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/ |title=CBS mourns longtime journalist Maria Mercader, who died at 54 from coronavirus|first=Hannah|last=Yasharoff |website=USA TODAY|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331021320/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/ |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] was dispatched to NYC to convert the {{convert|1800000|ft2|adj=on}} [[Javits Center]] into a 2,910-bed civilian medical hospital.<ref name=mashcivilian>{{cite web|url= https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/ |title=The Army Corps of Engineers has two or three weeks to get thousands of new hospital beds up and running|first=Meghann|last=Myers |date=March 27, 2020|website=Military Times|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330090248/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> More medical hospitals would be set up by these Army officers in New York City.<ref name=mashcivilian /> The {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} hospital ship arrived in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html Coronavirus live updates: USNS Comfort arrives in NYC; Anthony Fauci defends extension of social distancing rules; US deaths top 2,500] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330094014/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html |date=March 30, 2020 }} by John Bacon, USA TODAY, March 30, 2020</ref> It was also announced that [[field hospital]]s would be set up in [[Central Park]] in Manhattan and at the [[Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]] in Queens.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york |title=Central Park And Home Of Tennis' U.S. Open To House Hospital Beds For New York|first=Anastasia|last=Tsioulcas |publisher=NPR|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331113326/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Refrigerator trucks]] were set up on city streets outside hospitals to accommodate the bodies of the deceased.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403041350/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |archive-date=April 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was revealed that New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s brother [[Chris Cuomo]], who serves as a [[Cuomo Prime Time|CNN journalist]] and is a New York City resident, was diagnosed with COVID-19. The first death of a child from COVID-19 in New York City was recorded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff |title=NYC sees 1st child virus death; Chris Cuomo tests positive|agency=Associated Press|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331150103/https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:COVID19_Shuttered_Retailers_Unionport_-_The_Bronx_NY.jpg|thumb|Non-Essential retailers closed in Unionport, [[The Bronx]]]]\n\n=== April ===\nOn April 4, Cuomo announced that the Chinese government had arranged for a donation of 1,000 ventilators to be sent to New York through foundations run by [[Jack Ma]] and [[Joseph Tsai]].<ref name=\"ny0404\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/04/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-696ea085 |title=Coronavirus Hot Spots Emerging Near New York City |date=April 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> The state of Oregon was reported to be sending 140 ventilators.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/04/04/governor-cuomo-presser-4-4-2020 |title=Cuomo: 1,000 Ventilators Arriving From China, 140 From Oregon|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=NY1}}</ref> Trump announced that 1,000 additional federal medical soldiers would be deployed to NYC.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news12.com/story/41973252/president-trump-1000-military-personnel-deploying-to-nyc-to-help-in-covid19-hot-zone |title=President Trump: 1,000 military personnel deploying to NYC to help in COVID-19 hot zone |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> It was reported that \"Urban Area Medical Task Forces\" made up of army [[reservists]] would be working in arenas and convention centers that are serving as temporary field hospitals in NYC and other parts of the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/03/politics/us-military-additional-forces-coronavirus/index.html |title=US military preparing to deploy additional forces to support coronavirus response|date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|4|4|df=US|alt=As of April 4}}, there were 1,200 medical military personnel serving on the USNS ''Comfort''. 2,700 [[New York State National Guard]] forces had also been deployed.<ref name=\"ny0404\" />\n\nOn April 5, it was reported that a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] had contracted COVID-19, the first known case of a tiger anywhere being infected with the disease. Several other \"big cats\" were found to have COVID-19, the first of which had started showing symptoms on March 27; they were believed to have contracted COVID-19 from an infected zookeeper [[asymptomatic carrier|who was not yet showing symptoms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/tiger-nycs-bronx-zoo-tests-positive-coronavirus-69989185 |title=Tiger at NYC's Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|last1=PELTZ|first1=JENNIFER |date=5 April 2020|website=[[ABC News]]|language=en}}</ref> This is also the first known case of an animal contracting the disease from human contact in the US.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/#close |title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world |publisher=Nationalgeographic.com |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nOn April 6 there were 72,181 confirmed cases with at least 2,475 deaths. NYC accounted for 25% of COVID-19 deaths in the United States.<ref name=april6/>\n\nOn April 7 ''[[Gothamist]]'' reported that the death toll in New York City was undercounted.<ref name=gothamist>[https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths Staggering Surge Of NYers Dying In Their Homes Suggests City Is Undercounting Coronavirus Fatalities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408012523/https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |date=April 8, 2020 }} published on April 7, 2020 in ''The Gothamist''</ref>\nIt's estimated that 1,125 people have died at home or on the street in NYC in the first five days of April, an eightfold increase compared with FDNY figures for 2019. Due to the large increase, many of the deaths are presumed to be caused by COVID-19, but only residents with confirmed infections have been recorded in the official count. Due to crisis circumstances of the pandemic, the real death toll is unknown. Bodies of those who have died at home, around 280 per day, are being picked up by the US Army, National Guard and Air National Guard.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/nyregion/new-york-coronavirus-death-count.html |title=How Many People Have Actually Died From Coronavirus in New York? |date=April 10, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> \n\nAs of April 8, at least 80% of New York City virus patients put on ventilators had died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8ccd325c2be9bf454c2128dcb7bd616d|title=Some doctors moving away from ventilators for virus patients|date=April 8, 2020|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> Some of the communities most affected by the pandemic include densely-populated neighborhoods in north-central Queens with high immigrant populations, including [[Corona, Queens|Corona]], [[East Elmhurst, Queens|East Elmhurst]], [[Elmhurst, Queens|Elmhurst]], and [[Jackson Heights, Queens|Jackson Heights]]. {{As of|2020|April|8|alt=As of April 8}}, these communities, with a cumulative 600,000 residents, had recorded 7,260 COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correal|first=Annie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/nyregion/coronavirus-queens-corona-jackson-heights-elmhurst.html|title=\u2018A Tragedy Is Unfolding\u2019: Inside New York\u2019s Virus Epicenter|date=2020-04-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|last2=Jacobs|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Jones|first3=Ryan Christopher}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, it was reported that at least 41 MTA workers had died from COVID-19 and 1,500 have tested positive. Riders on the subway had decreased by 92%.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abc7ny.com/coronavirus-new-york-ny-cases-in-news/6086749/ |title=Coronavirus News: MTA death toll hits 41, with 1,500 positive cases |date=April 8, 2020 |publisher=ABC}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{seealso|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\n[[File:Coronavirus sign in Brooklyn (60539).jpg|thumb|Woman wearing a mask walks under the Cobble Hill Cinemas in [[Brooklyn]], which closed as a non-essential business.]]\n\nOn March 2, de Blasio [[Twitter|tweeted]] that people should ignore the virus and \"go on with your lives + get out on the town despite Coronavirus\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |title=De Blasio haunted by weeks-old tweet urging people to 'get out on the town despite coronavirus' |date=March 25, 2020 |first1=Madison |last1=Dibble |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329063537/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 4, [[Commissioner of Health of the City of New York|New York City Commissioner of Health]] [[Oxiris Barbot]] said: \"There\u2019s no indication that being in a car, being in the subways with someone who\u2019s potentially sick is a risk factor.\"<ref name=\"nypost1\"/> New York City Councilmen Democrat [[Robert Holden (politician)|Robert Holden]] and Republican [[Eric Ulrich]] wrote to Mayor de Blasio asking him to relieve Barbot of her position \"before it\u2019s too late,\" saying her guidance on coronavirus had been disastrous.<ref name=\"nypost1\">{{cite web|last=Edelman |first=Susan |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/04/nyc-pols-urge-de-blasio-to-oust-health-commissioner-over-coronavirus-response/ |title=NYC pols urge de Blasio to oust health commissioner over coronavirus response |work=New York Post |date=April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, [[Governor of New York|Governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] declared a [[state of emergency]] in New York State after 89 cases had been confirmed in the state, 70 of them in [[Westchester County]], 12 in New York City, and 7 elsewhere.<ref name=\"state-emergency\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 8, 2020 |title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Cuomo Declares State of Emergency |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |work=The New York Times |location= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309082540/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n===PAUSE order===\nOn March 14, before the PAUSE order was put in place, all [[New York Public Library]] branches in the Bronx, Manhattan and Staten Island were temporarily closed. The [[Queens Public Library]] and [[Brooklyn Public Library]] were also closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schuessler|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|title=At the Library, Last Call for Beauty and Books|date=March 14, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|title=Queens Public Library closed until further notice|website=Queens Daily Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033712/https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|title=Brooklyn Public Library Closes Doors Over Coronavirus|date=March 16, 2020|website=Prospect Heights-Crown Heights, NY Patch|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Theaters, concert venues and nightclubs in NYC have been shutdown since March 17, and restaurants were restricted to take out and delivery only.  Schools were closed until at least April 20.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-new-york-city-close-all-theaters-restaurants-take-out-delivery-only/ |title=New York City to close all theaters and shift restaurants to take-out and delivery only due to coronavirus |date=March 16, 2020 |publisher=CBS News}}</ref> Gyms were closed as well.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-city-shelter-in-place-governor-andrew-cuomo-mayor-bill-de-blasio/ |title=New York governor dismisses idea of NYC shelter-in-place order hours after mayor said to prepare for it |date=March 18, 2020 |publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, despite de Blasio's message to New Yorkers that they should be \"prepared right now\" for the possibility of \"shelter in place\" orders, Cuomo expressed doubts about whether the policy would be effective. The governor's office issued a statement that the shelter in place order could only be put in place by the governor's office; the Mayor's office agreed.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/new-york-city-mayor-says-shelter-place-decision-coming-next-n1161516 |title=New York mayor says 'shelter in place' decision coming in next 48 hours |date=March 17, 2020 |publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20th, with 5,683 confirmed cases in NYC, the governor's office issued an executive order that shelter in place restrictions would go into effect on March 22nd at 8PM. The order put in place the following restrictions:<ref name=sip>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage|title=43 Coronavirus Deaths and Over 5,600 Cases in N.Y.C.|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>\n#Anyone with underlying conditions, a compromised immune system, or who is over the age of 70 should wear a mask.\n#Healthy persons should limit their outdoor activities to getting groceries and medicine.\n#Exercising and walking outdoors in permitted as long as social distancing is observed and participants stay at least six feet away from each other.\n#No nonessential gatherings of any size\n#Mass transit should not be used unless absolutely necessary. Roads remain open.\n#Nonessential workers must stay home. \n\nThe governor said the provisions would be enforced. Businesses that violate the order face fines and closure.<ref name=sip/> \"This is not life as usual\" the governor said, \"accept it and realize it and deal with it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-shelter-in-place-coronavirus.html |title=It\u2019s Not \u2018Shelter in Place\u2019: What the New Coronavirus Restrictions Mean |date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nBusinesses that qualify as \"essential businesses\" under the shelter in place order include:<ref name=sip/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*utility companies\n*banks\n*pharmacies\n*laundromats\n*gas stations\n*grocers, restaurants and convenience stores\n*liquor stores\n*hardware stores\n*auto repair shops\n*delivery services\n*skilled contractors like plumbers\n*health care providers\n*warehouses\n*manufacturers\n*construction companies\n*animal-care providers\n}}\n\nOn April 6, the statewide PAUSE order was extended through April 29. The rate of increase had slowed from 10,000 new confirmed cases daily to 8,700. Intubation and ICU admission rates were slowing. Fines for violating social distancing protocols were increased from $500 to $1000.<ref name=april6>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/our-9-11-moment-new-york-braces-as-nations-top-doctor-warns-saddest-week-ahead/2361336/ |title=\u2018No Time to Be Lax:\u2019 Cuomo Extends New York Shutdown, NJ Deaths Top 1,000 |date=April 6, 2020 |publisher=NBC}}</ref>\n\n===Public health===\n[[File:New York National Guard - 49738408268.jpg|thumb|The \"Javits New York Medical Station\" is a [[field hospital]] set up in the [[Javits Center]]]]\nIn response to the increasing number of coronavirus cases at the end of March 2020, several temporary [[field hospital]]s were built or proposed, including the Javits Center in Manhattan,<ref name=mashcivilian/> [[USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]] in Queens (350 beds),<ref>{{Cite news|last=Honan|first=Katie|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068 |title=Queens Stadium to Be Converted Into Temporary Hospital in Coronavirus Fight|date=March 30, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331001258/https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068 |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and in [[Central Park]] in Manhattan (68-bed COVID respiratory care unit).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whec.com/national/central-park-houses-hospital-ward-as-ny-races-to-add-beds/5690659/ |title=Central Park houses hospital ward as NY races to add beds |publisher=WHEC.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html |title=Central Park becomes a field hospital for New York, where coronavirus deaths have topped 1,000|last=Holcombe|first=Madeline |last2=Yan|first2=Holly |date=March 30, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330123931/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Field hospitals were also proposed at the [[New York Expo Center]] in the Bronx, [[Aqueduct Racetrack]] in Queens, the [[Brooklyn Cruise Terminal]], and the [[College of Staten Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/ |title=Governor calls on federal government to authorize more field hospitals in New York City|date=March 27, 2020|website=amNewYork|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055138/https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/ |archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAt the request of the Mayor, [[Veterinarian|veterinary clinics]] sent their [[ventilator]]s to human hospitals.<ref name=nyp2020-04-01>{{cite web |last1=Fonrouge |first1=Gabrielle |title=NYC veterinarians forced to choose people over pets in war against coronavirus |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |website=[[New York Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403091741/https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |archivedate=April 2, 2020 |language=en |date=April 1, 2020 |quote=Last week, Blue Pearl Veterinary Partners donated seven of their ventilators to New York-Presbyterian Hospital in Manhattan |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5 a state Health Department official confirmed that seriously ill patients were bring treated with [[hydroxychloroquine]]. The effects are being observed by the [[University of Albany]]'s School of Public Health.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/05/ny-coronavirus-patients-being-treated-with-anti-malarial-drug/ |title=Thousands of NY COVID patients are being treated with anti-malarial drug |date=April 5, 2020 |publisher=The New York Post}}</ref>\n\nDue to the demand from the pandemic on New York City hospitals,  [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] personnel were ordered not to transport adult [[cardiac arrest]] cases to the hospital, if the personnel were unable to restart the patient's heart at the scene.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.salon.com/2020/04/07/first-responders-suspect-crazy-increase-in-cardiac-deaths-in-nyc-is-linked-to-covid-19/?fbclid=IwAR2MfEvJ688AaFHPgVNLSXfnF2e8vskieeOm5yqGBWeAQMRuVS-0MlCnQUg |title=First responders suspect \"crazy increase in cardiac deaths\" in NYC is linked to COVID-19 |publisher=Salon.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\nAccording to new projections, taking into account the effects of the PAUSE order, NYC is expected to need around 20,000 hospital beds instead of 111,000.<ref name=april6/> \n\nThe New York City healthcare system continues to experience major shortages with its COVID-19 testing capacity. An alert sent out on April 11, 2020 by city's Department of Health and Mental Hygiene stated that the city's hospitals are close to running out of [[cotton swab]]s used for COVID-19 testing. The same alert reminded the providers that only those patients admitted for hospitalization should be given COVID-19 tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2020/04/11/new-york-hospitals-could-soon-completely-run-out-of-swabs-needed-for-coronavirus-testing-1274903|title=New York hospitals could soon 'completely run out' of swabs needed for coronavirus testing|author=Joe Anuta|work=[[Politico]]|date=2020-04-11|access-date=2020-04-12}} </ref>\n\n=== Public transport ===\n[[File:MTA New York City Transit Sanitizes Stations and Subway Cars (49618677077).jpg|thumb|Disinfection of [[New York City Subway rolling stock|New York City Subway cars]] against coronavirus]]\nNew York City issued new commuter guidelines amid the current outbreak, asking sick individuals to stay off public transit, encouraging citizens to avoid densely packed buses, [[New York City Subway|subways]], and trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/nyc-issues-new-commuter-guidelines-to-combat-coronavirus-spread/2317584/|title=NYC Issues New Commuter Guidelines to Combat Coronavirus Spread|website=NBC New York|language=en-US|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Due to decreasing ridership, amid an existing [[2017 New York City transit crisis|transit crisis]], service on buses, subways, and [[commuter rail]] was reduced starting on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|title=Coronavirus New York: MTA launches essential schedule amid COVID-19 crisis|date=March 24, 2020|website=ABC7 New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326080255/https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|title=MTA Slashes Service, NJ Transit on Reduced Schedules|date=March 24, 2020|website=NBC New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033708/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 8, all NYC school trips were canceled.<ref name=\"NewYork38\">[https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ Coronavirus Update: Cuomo Calls For Private Testing To Match Demand, Wife Of New Rochelle Victim Speaks, Schools Close] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309152732/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ |date=March 9, 2020 }} [[WCBS-TV|CBS 2]]/[[WLNY-TV|WLNY TV 10/55]]</ref> On March 13, De Blasio stated that he would keep the schools open, citing the need for [[school meal]] programs and [[child care]] to continue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|title=Coronavirus outbreak: NYC teachers 'furious' over de Blasio's policy to keep schools open|last=|first=|date=March 13, 2020|website=|publisher=NBCnews.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325232502/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> On March 15, all schools in the [[New York City Department of Education]] system closed until at least mid-April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|title=New York City Public Schools to Close to Slow Spread of Coronavirus|date=March 15, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326170024/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Closed playground in New York City on April 1st, 2020.jpg|thumb|Closed playground in New York City on April 2nd, 2020 due to the 2019-2020 COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn April 1, Governor Cuomo ordered all playgrounds in the city to be shut in order to promote [[social distancing]]. Parks will remain open.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnard |first1=Anne |last2=Schweber |first2=Nate |title=Cooped-Up Children Lose Refuge as N.Y.C. Playgrounds Are Closed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-playgrounds-closed.html?action=click&module=News&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, Mayor Bill de Blasio ordered all schools to remain closed for the rest of year, while Gov. Cuomo insisted that the authority to close and reopen schools throughout the state belonged to himself as the governor, not to de Blasio or any other mayor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|title=New York City Schools Are Closed for Rest of Academic Year|date=2020-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html|title=Cuomo Urges Caution on Rush to Reopen N.Y.: Live Updates|date=2020-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Temporary burials===\n[[File:COVID-19 burials on Hart Island.webm|thumb|COVID-19 burials on Hart Island]]\nOn April 6, the ''New York Times'' reported that the city's overall death rate had tripled and that morgues were overwhelmed. After councilman [[Mark D. Levine]] tweeted that temporary internment \"likely will be done by using a NYC park for burials\", NYC officials said they were not considering temporary burials in city parks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marsh |first=Julia |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/06/nyc-to-begin-temporarily-burying-coronavirus-victims-in-local-parks/ |title=NYC may temporarily bury coronavirus victims on Hart Island |publisher=Nypost.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/nyc-to-start-temporary-burials-for-covid-19-victims-likely-in-trenches-in-nyc-parks-levine/2361777/ |title=Temporary Burials Possible for COVID-19 Victims, But NYC Park Trenches Plan Denied |date=April 6, 2020 |publisher=NBC}}</ref>\n\nThe mayor's press secretary said that a next resort could be to store or bury bodies on [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart Island]] off the coast of the Bronx in the [[Long Island Sound]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/nyregion/mass-graves-nyc-parks-coronavirus.html |title=New York City Considers Temporary Graves for Virus Victims|date=2020-04-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|last2=Stack|first2=Liam |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following reports that mass burials had begun there,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52241221|title=New York digging mass graves amid virus outbreak|date=10 April 2020|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"gothamist2\">{{cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |title=Mass Burials On Hart Island Increase Fivefold As COVID-19 Death Toll Skyrockets|date=9 April 2020|website=Gothamist |language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200410110654/https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref> the mayor clarified that Hart Island was only being used for unclaimed bodies or for those who chose it as a burial place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/new-york-coronavirus-cases-burials-bodies-covid-19-hart-island-a9459956.html |title=New York rules out mass Covid burials but admits 'devastating' Hart Island pictures are \u2018unclaimed\u2019 victims|date=2020-04-10|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Social impact==\n\n===Social distancing===\n[[File:Line at Costco (90265).jpg|thumb|Line at [[Costco]] in Brooklyn on March 19]] \nOn March 28, a Brooklyn bar owner, 56-year-old Vasil Pando, was arrested for defying Governor Andrew Cuomo's ban on bars and restaurants until April 15. Pando was charged with \"illegal sale of alcohol, promoting gambling, and violating the mayor's {{sic|expected=governor's}} order\".<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html Coronavirus: New York bar owner becomes first to be arrested for ignoring lockdown] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331140449/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html|date=March 31, 2020}} by Gino Spocchia, The Independent, March 30, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the mayor announced that most religious buildings had shut down in accordance with quarantine regulations. However, he warned that some churches and synagogues were not in compliance and would be shut down by authorities if they remained open.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/NYC-Mayor-to-synagogues-Close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767|title=NYC mayor to synagogues: Close for coronavirus or shut down permanently|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330194032/https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/nyc-mayor-to-synagogues-close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn April 3, the NYPD broke up a party in the Bronx where several dozen people had gathered in violation of social distancing rules. Two men were arrested and charged with multiple violations, while dozens more were given a summons for violation of social distancing rules.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/04/nypd-busts-bronx-party-ignoring-coronavirus-social-distancing-rules/|title=Cops bust boozy Bronx party ignoring coronavirus social distancing rules|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=New Yor Post}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7 NBC news reported violations of the statewide PAUSE order throughout NYC. Workers in [[Pelham Bay (neighborhood), Bronx|Pelham Bay, Bronx]], put netting around outdoor gym areas to prevent groups from gathering. De Blasio said violations of the order could be reported to 311.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/chopper-video-shows-crowded-nyc-parks-despite-cuomo-extending-pause-order/2362986/ |title=Chopper Video Shows Large Groups at NYC Parks Despite Cuomo Extending PAUSE Order |date=April 7, 2020 |publisher=NBC}}</ref>\n\nOne epidemiologist at Columbia University noted \"Social distancing is a privilege that not everybody has equal opportunity to practice.\" Of the five boroughs, Manhattan has reported the fewest number of confirmed cases. Epidemiologists have observed that low income communities are being disproportionately affected. Many residents of these neighborhoods work in essential jobs where it may not be possible to work from home.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/04/07/why-manhattan-has-seen-relatively-few-coronavirus-cases |title=Why Manhattan Has Seen Relatively Few Coronavirus Cases |date=April 8, 2020 |publisher=NY1}}</ref>\n\n===Police and crime===\nAt the beginning of March, prior to the confirmation of the first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], and the onset of the coronavirus pandemic in New York City, a 20 percent spike in crime for the first two months of 2020 was reported.<ref>{{cite web|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|title=Data: NYC serious crimes spikes in first 2 months of 2020|website=[[Newsday]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303190943/https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After movement in the city became restricted, [[NYPD]] Commissioner [[Dermot Shea]] stated that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|public health crisis]] had curtailed crime.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Ben|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|title=New York City Crime Falls as Coronavirus Takes Hold|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326034158/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of the month, [[9-1-1|911]] calls were at a record high, and 1,048 officers and 145 civilian employees had tested positive for COVID-19. 5,657 uniformed officers, or more than 15% of the force, called out sick on March 31.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html More than 1,000 New York City police officers have the coronavirus as 911 calls hit record highs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401213545/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html |date=April 1, 2020 }} by William Feuer, [[CNBC]], April 1, 2020</ref> The percentage of officers out sick rose to nearly 20 percent, as reported on April 6.<ref>{{cite web| author=Craig McCarthy and Julia Marsh|title=Huge percentage of NYPD cops out sick as coronavirus spreads |website=New York Post |date=April 6, 2020 |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/06/nearly-20-percent-of-nypd-cops-are-out-sick-during-coronavirus-outbreak/}}</ref>  As of April 8, 2,103 uniformed members and 373 civilian members have tested positive for the virus while 13 have died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.silive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-132-new-nypd-members-test-positive-for-covid-19-13th-death-in-the-department-reported.html |author=Irene Spezzamonte|title=Coronavirus: 132 new NYPD members test positive for COVID-19, 13th death in the department reported |website=Staten Island Advance|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Hospitals==\n\nNew York City usually has about 20,000 hospital beds and 5,000 ventilators, many of which are routinely in use to keep ICU patients alive. Social distancing measures were implemented to slow the spread of the virus and prevent the hospital system from collapsing.<ref name=nytimes_march14>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-hospitals.html |title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Will a Surge in Patients Overwhelm Hospitals? |date=March 14, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn the early days of the crisis, on March 14, the [[Health and Hospitals Corporation]] and [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital|New York-Presbyterian]] cancelled non-emergency surgeries. [[Northwell Health]] put out a call for retired nurses to return. The [[Tisch Hospital]] of [[NYU Langone]] converted a pediatric emergency ward into a respiratory ward. Personal protective equipment was rationed due to shortages.<ref name=nytimes_march14/> By March 25 the situation at [[Elmhurst Hospital]], one of the worst affected hospitals in the city, had deteriorated enough that staff described it as \"apocalyptic.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/nyc-coronavirus-hospitals.html |title=13 Deaths in a Day: An \u2018Apocalyptic\u2019 Coronavirus Surge at an N.Y.C. Hospital |date=March 25, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors have been trying to crowdsource tablets so patients can say goodbye to loved ones. The last contact patients have with their families is when they are dropped off at the hospital or taken by ambulance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/04/10/coronavirus-new-york-hospitals-ipads-tablets/ |title=Coronavirus Update: New Yorkers Donate Tablets To Hospitals So COVID-19 Patients Can Say Goodbye To Family Members |date=April 10, 2020 |publisher=CBS local}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the number of new patients admitted to the hospital began increasing at a decreasing rate in early April, Cuomo stated that social distancing protocols would continue to be enforced to prevent a rise in these figures that could overwhelm the strained healthcare system.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html |title=Hospitalizations for Coronavirus Are Nearly Flat in N.Y., but 799 More Die |date=April 9, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> \n\n{{As of|2020|4|9|df=US}} the USNS ''Comfort'' had only 20 patients despite a 1,000 bed capacity. The ''Comfort'' was originally intended to take noncoronavirus patients to ease the burden on city hospitals, but most New Yorkers remain isolated in their homes and non-COVID admissions have decreased dramatically. The admission process for the few non-COVID patients who do present at the ER has been cumbersome. Ambulances are not permitted to take patients to the ship; they must first be evaluated at city hospitals and tested for the virus because no one with coronavirus is allowed on board the ship. There are 49 additional medical conditions that also meet the exclusion criteria for admission to the ''Comfort''. Though the Javits Center was similarly intended to treat non-COVID cases, Cuomo reached an agreement with Trump to allow admission of COVID patients at the field hospital.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-usns-comfort.html |title=The 1,000-Bed Comfort Was Supposed to Aid New York. It Has 20 Patients. |date=April 7, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nOn April 5, it was reported that 51% of COVID-19 cases in NYC were at least 50 years old.<ref name=april6/> In previous weeks, the majority of cases had been men between 18 and 49 years of age.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/20/majority-of-nycs-coronavirus-cases-are-men-between-18-and-49-years-old/ |title=Majority of NYC\u2019s coronavirus cases are men between 18 and 49 years old  |date=March 20, 2020 |publisher=New Yor Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://abc7ny.com/cuomo-new-york-coronavirus-in/6038951/ |title=Coronavirus Updates: People 18-49 represent 53% of coronavirus cases in New York |publisher=ABC}}</ref>\n\n==Data==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/New York State/New York City medical cases chart}}\n{{-}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in New York City\nUpdated 4/14/2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|title=COVID-19: Data - NYC Health|website=www1.nyc.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n!Borough\n!Cases\n!Cases per 100,000\n!Hospitalizations\n!Deaths\n|-\n|Bronx\n|23,426\n|1,591\n|6,796\n|1,512\n|-\n|Brooklyn\n|28,183\n|1,038\n|7,609\n|1,869\n|-\n|Manhattan\n|13,740\n|730\n|3,946\n|756\n|-\n|Queens\n|33,616\n|1,342\n|9,789\n|2,105\n|-\n|Staten Island\n|8,236\n|1,644\n|1,358\n|345\n|-\n|Unassigned\n|62\n| -\n|13\n|2\n|-\n|Total\n|107,263\n| -\n|29,511\n|6,589\n|}\n\n==Graphs==\nAdapted from nyc.gov.<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\" /> Note that the cases are by date of diagnosis, and deaths are by date of death. Due to delays in reporting, historical counts may be subject to change and recent data may be incomplete. \n\n=== Cases over time ===\n<!-- Data lives on Commons. Per talk page, do NOT add counts for the current or previous day, since they are incomplete and can throw off the charts -->\n{{Graph:Lines\n| table=COVID-19 cases in New York City.tab\n| type=time\n| xField=date\n| series=\"cases_per_day\"\n| title=New COVID-19 cases announced each day in New York City\n| yZero=false\n| xAxis=Date\n| xTicks=-\n| yAxis=Confirmed cases\n| yMax=\n| yGrid=y\n| width=1100\n| barwidth=14\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Lines\n| table=COVID-19 cases in New York City.tab\n| type=time\n| xField=date\n| series=\"deaths_per_day\"\n| title=New COVID-19 deaths each day in New York City\n| yZero=false\n| xAxis=Date\n| xTicks=-\n| yAxis=Deaths\n| yMax=\n| yGrid=y\n| width=1100\n| barwidth=14\n}}\n\n=== Cases by demographic ===\n\n{{col-float|1=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=pie\n|width=100\n|height=100\n|legend=Cases by borough\n|x=Queens (34831), Brooklyn (29250), The Bronx (24587), Manhattan (14188), Staten Island (8504),Unknown (64)\n|y=34831,29250,24587,14188,8504,64\n|showValues=\n}}\n|2=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=pie\n|width=100\n|height=100\n|legend=Cases by age group\n|x=0 to 17 (2150), 18 to 44 (42127), 45 to 64 (40559), 65 to 74 (14025), 75 an