n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Punk rock]], [[pop punk]], [[alternative rock]], [[garage rock]], [[alternative metal]]\n| length       = 56:35\n| language     = [[Japanese language|Japanese]], English\n| label        = Sub Trax\n| producer     = Kenta Matsukuma, JxSxK\n| prev_title   = [[Brand-new idol Shit (album)|Brand-new idol SHiT]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = [[Killer BiSH|KiLLER BiSH]]\n| next_year    = 2016\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = FAKE METAL JACKET\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = OTNK\n | single1date = September 2, 2015\n}}\n}}\n'''''Fake Metal Jacket''''' (stylized as '''''FAKE METAL JACKET''''') is the second album by Japanese idol group [[BiSH|Bish]] released through the independent label Sub Trax on January 20, 2016. The album is the first full album by the group to feature Lingling and Hashiyasume Atsuko, who joined the group on August 5, 2015. The album features four re-recorded versions of tracks from their first album, updated to feature the two new members. Like their debut album [[Brand-new idol Shit (album)|Brand-new idol Shit]], songs from the album were posted for streaming on [[SoundCloud]] little by little on the group's account as well as being released as free downloads on Ototoy for a limited time. All new songs from the album were eventually streamable, and the music videos for both the new version of \"MONSTERS\", and \"ALL YOU NEED IS LOVE\" were uploaded on YouTube. The album was preceded by the single \"OTNK\", released on September 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u65b0\u66f2\u5168\u767a\u8868\uff01BiSH\u30012nd\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u66f2\u300c\u30c7\u30d1\u30fc\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30ba\u300d\u300cDEAR\u2026\u300d\u516c\u958b|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/172479|website=\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BiSH\u65b0\u4f5c\u53ce\u9332\u66f2\u300cMONSTERS\u300d\u30a2\u30b0\u30ec\u30c3\u30b7\u30d6\u306a\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u516c\u958b|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/171774|website=\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| headline = \n| title1          = Spark\n| lyrics1         = JxSxK\n| music1          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note1          = \u30b9\u30d1\u30fc\u30af\n| length1         = 5:35\n\n| title2          = BiSH -Hoshi ga Matataku Yoru ni-\n| lyrics2         = Bish & JxSxK & Kenta Matsukuma\n| music2          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note2          = {{nihongo2|BiSH -\u661f\u304c\u77ac\u304f\u591c\u306b-; \"BiSH: On a Night When Stars are Twinkling\"}}\n| length2         = 4:37\n\n| title3          = MONSTERS\n| lyrics3         = Yukako Love Deluxe\n| music3          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| length3         = 3:30\n\n| title4          = Primitive\n| lyrics4         = Hashiyasume Atsuko & JxSxK\n| music4          = Ichiro Iguchi\n| length4         = 4:46\n\n| title5          = beautiful sa\n| lyrics5         = Lingling\n| music5          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note5         = beautiful\u3055\n| length5         = 4:37\n\n| title6          = OTNK\n| lyrics6         = Iku Ryukyuji\n| music6          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| length6         = 4:02\n\n| title7          = Migatte I Need You\n| lyrics7         = Hug Mii\n| music7          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note7          = \u8eab\u52dd\u624b\u3042\u3044\u306b\u30fc\u3058\u3085\u30fc\n| length7         = 3:27\n\n| title8          = Departures\n| lyrics8         = Momoko Gumi Company\n| music8          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note8          = \u30c7\u30d1\u30fc\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30ba\n| length8         = 3:45\n\n| title9          = Want\n| lyrics9         = Momoko Gumi Company\n| music9          = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note9         = \u30a6\u30a9\u30f3\u30c8\n| length9         = 3:39\n\n| title10         = Saraba Kana\n| lyrics10        = Iku Ryukyuji\n| music10        = Shinnosuke (from Mushi Furuu Yoru ni)\n| note10          = \u30b5\u30e9\u30d0\u304b\u306a\n| length10        = 4:41\n\n| title11         = ALL YOU NEED IS LOVE\n| lyrics11        = Bish & JxSxK & Kenta Matsukuma\n| music11         = Kenta Matsukuma\n| length11        = 4:55\n\n| title12         = DEAR...\n| lyrics12        = Momoko Gumi Company\n| music12         = Kenta Matsukuma\n| length12        = 4:36\n\n| title13         = BUDOKAN ka Moshiku wa TAMANEGI\n| lyrics13        = Cent Chihiro Chittiii & JxSxK & Kenta Matsukuma\n| music13         = Kenta Matsukuma\n| note13        = BUDOKAN\u304b\u3082\u3057\u304f\u306fTAMANEGI\n| length13        = 4:29\n|all_writing=|total_length=}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[BiSH|Bish]] - [[lyricist|Lyrics]] on Track 2\n**Cent Chihiro Chittiii \u2013 [[vocals]]; lyrics on Track 13\n**Aina The End \u2013 vocals\n**Momoko Gumi Company - vocals; lyrics on Tracks 8, 9 and 12\n**Hug Mii - vocals; lyrics on Track 7\n**Lingling - vocals; lyrics on Track 5\n**Hashiyasume Atsuko - vocals; lyrics on Track 4\n*Ex. Bish\n**Yukako Love Deluxe - lyrics on Track 3\n\n==Notes==\n*All writing, arrangement and personnel credits taken from the album insert.<ref>\n{{cite AV media notes\n| title      = Fake Metal Jacket\n| others    = BiSH\n| date      = 2016\n| type    = CD liner\n| publisher = SUB TRAX\n| id       = DDCZ-2069\n| location  = Japan\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{BiSH}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fake Metal Jacket}}\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n[[Category:BiSH albums]]\n", "name_user": "Ganbaruby", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonnel:linking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fake_Metal_Jacket"}
{"title_page": "Mehmet Oz", "text_new": "{{short description|Turkish-American medical doctor and television host}}\n{{Redirect|Dr. Oz|the syndicated talk series|The Dr. Oz Show}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mehmet \u00d6z\n| image       = Mehmet Oz official photo.jpg\n| birth_name = Mehmet Cengiz \u00d6z\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Talk show host, surgeon,  author\n| children = 4, including [[Daphne Oz]]\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Lisa Oz|Lisa Lemole]]|1985}}\n| years_active = 1982\u2013present\n| education  = [[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] {{small|([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}\n| website  = {{url|doctoroz.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Mehmet Cengiz \u00d6z''' ({{IPA-tr|meh\u02c8met d\u0292e\u0272\u02c8\u025fiz \u0153z|lang}}; born June 11, 1960),<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web| url=https://www.biography.com/personality/dr-oz|title=Dr. Oz (1960\u2013)|publisher=[[Biography.com]]|accessdate= October 13, 2019|archivedate=June 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190612173946/https://www.biography.com/personality/dr-oz|url-status=live}}</ref> known professionally as '''Dr. Oz''', is a [[Turkish Americans|Turkish American]]<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1688472/Mehmet-Oz |title=Mehmet Oz biography \u2013 Turkish American surgeon, educator, and author |first=Amy |last=Tikkanen |encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |year=2015 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> [[television personality]], [[cardiothoracic surgeon]], [[Columbia University]] professor,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://columbiasurgery.org/mehmet-c-oz-md-facs|title=Mehmet C. Oz, MD, FACS {{!}} Columbia University Department of Surgery|website=columbiasurgery.org|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> [[pseudoscience]] promoter,<ref name=\"Salon2015\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.salon.com/2015/04/17/physicians_urge_columbia_to_drop_its_unacceptable_affiliation_with_pseudoscience_promoter_dr_oz/|title=Physicians urge Columbia to drop its \"unacceptable\" affiliation with pseudoscience promoter Dr. Oz|last=Abrams|first=Lindsay|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=2017-06-19|date=2015-04-17}}</ref> journalist, and [[author]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsmax.com/FastFeatures/Green-Coffee-Beans-Extract-Reviews-Congress-Investigation-Supplements/2015/03/16/id/630396/|title=Green Coffee Beans Extract Reviews: What Congress Found In Its Investigation|work=Newsmax|access-date=2017-06-19}}</ref> In 2003, [[Oprah Winfrey]] was the first guest on the [[Discovery Channel]] series ''Second Opinion with Dr. Oz'',<ref name=oprah>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oprah.com/health/dr-oz-and-oprah-interview-how-to-find-balance-in-your-life/all |title=Dr. Oz Talks to Oprah About Food, Family and What It Really Means to Be Healthy |publisher=Oprah.com |language=en-us |access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> and, since 2004, Oz became a regular guest on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', making more than sixty appearances.<ref name=oprah/> In 2009, ''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'', a daily television program focusing on medical issues and personal health, was launched by Winfrey's [[Harpo Productions]] and [[Sony Pictures Television]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/pressroom/pressrelease/20080613_orig_drozsony|title=Harpo Productions and Sony Pictures Television To Launch Dr. Oz|work=Oprah.com|date=June 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe is a proponent of [[alternative medicine]], and has been criticized by physicians, government officials, and publications, including ''[[Popular Science]]'' and ''[[The New Yorker]]'', for endorsing unproven products and non-scientific advice. The ''[[British Medical Journal]]'' published a study that found more than half of the recommendations on medical talk series like ''The Dr. Oz Show'' had either no evidence or contradicted medical research.<ref name=\"mehmetpost\" />  [[Donald Trump]]'s appointment of Oz to the Council on Sports, Fitness, and Nutrition was criticized as an example of choosing \"pundits over experts\".<ref name=intelligencer /><ref name=fast>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40568706/heres-why-dr-oz-is-an-absurd-choice-for-trumps-health-council |title=Here's Why Dr. Oz Is An Absurd Choice For Trump's Health Council |last=Raphael |first=Rina |date=2018-05-07 |website=Fast Company |language=en-US |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nOz was born in 1960 in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], to Suna and Mustafa \u00d6z, who had emigrated from [[Konya Province]], [[Turkey]].<ref name=gma20090831>{{cite news|first=Lana|last=Zak|title=Dr. Oz on Complementary Medicine: 'Challenge the Status Quo'|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/OnCall/story?id=8450292|work=Good Morning America|date = August 31, 2009|access-date= October 12, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Faces\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/profiles/dr-mehmet-oz/4/ |title=Faces of America: Dr. Mehmet Oz |work=[[Faces of America (PBS series)|Faces of America]]'' series, with Professor [[Henry Louis Gates|Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] |year=2010}}</ref> Mustafa, born in [[Bozk\u0131r]], a small town in southern Turkey, earned scholarships that allowed him to emigrate to the United States as a [[Residency (medicine)|medical resident]] in 1955. Suna (n\u00e9e Atabay), who comes from a wealthy [[Istanbul]] family, is the daughter of a [[pharmacist]] with [[Circassians|Circassian]] ([[Shapsug]]) descent on her mother's side. Oz has two sisters, Seval \u00d6z and Nazlim \u00d6z.<ref name=\"Faces\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Dr. Mehmet \u00d6z'\u00fcn D\u00fczce'ye uzanan soya\u011fac\u0131 |url=http://jinepsgazetesi.com/index.php?module=news&news_id=11655&cat_id=106 |work=Jineps |date= January 1, 2011 |access-date= September 17, 2011 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\nOz was educated at [[Tower Hill School]] in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]].<ref name=\"PhillyInterview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/exit-interview-dr-oz/ | title=Exit Interview: Dr. Oz | publisher=[[Metrocorp]] | work=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia]] | date=October 30, 2009 | access-date=March 11, 2014 | last=Rys |first=Richard}}</ref> In 1982, he received his undergraduate degree in biology at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=7641721&privcapId=79086309&previousCapId=29249600&previousTitle=The%20Cue%20Ball%20Group,%20LLC|work=Business Week |title= Executive Profile: Mehmet C. Oz M.D |access-date=January 12, 2011}}</ref> He played safety on Harvard's football team and won an intramural college championship playing water polo.<ref name=\"charlotte\"/> In 1986, he obtained [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] and [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] degrees, respectively, at the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]]<ref name=\"PhillyInterview\"/> and Penn's [[Wharton School]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Lizzy |last=Ratner |title=The Great and Powerful Dr. Oz |url=http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/great-and-powerful-dr-oz |work=[[New York Observer]] |date= August 14, 2007 |access-date= September 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020021729/http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/great-and-powerful-dr-oz |archive-date=October 20, 2007 }}</ref> He was awarded the Captain's Athletic Award for leadership in college<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.abc.daytonsnewssource.com/sections/entertainment/droz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704070306/http://abc.daytonsnewssource.com/sections/entertainment/droz/ | year=2010| publisher= WKEF-TV |archive-date= July 4, 2010 | title= Mehmet C. Oz, M.D.}}</ref> and was [[class president]] and then [[student body president]] during medical school.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.talkshows.about.com/od/thedrozshow/p/DrOzBio.htm |title= Dr Oz \u2013 The Dr Oz Show |publisher= about.com |access-date= May 22, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160120093331/http://talkshows.about.com/od/thedrozshow/p/DrOzBio.htm |archive-date= January 20, 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dr. Oz at ServiceNation 2008.jpg|thumb|Mehmet Oz at [[ServiceNation]] in 2008]]\n\n===Medical===\nIn 1996, Ottavio Alfieri proposed to Oz that the mitral valve only needed one suture to close a leak. He developed the idea to use a catheter to put one staple in and submitted the patent for [[MitraClip]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/703961/ccopelan/how-dr-oz-kick-started-a-groundbreaking-device-for-patients-with-heart-failure/|title=How Dr. Oz Kick-Started a Groundbreaking Device for Patients with Heart Failure|author=Copelan, Christine|date=26 September 2018|work=Parade}}</ref> In the late 1990s, Oz began recommending [[ventricular assist device]]s as an alternative for patients with heart failure.<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/eheart/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Oz joined [[Jeff Arnold (Internet entrepreneur)|Jeff Arnold]] as co-founder of [[Sharecare|Sharecare, Inc.]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health2con.com/news/2010/10/18/san-francisco-2010-launch-of-sharecare/ |title=Sharecare, Inc. |publisher=Health 2.0 |access-date=March 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208104438/http://www.health2con.com/news/2010/10/18/san-francisco-2010-launch-of-sharecare/ |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> providing an interactive question and answer platform for industry experts to answer health-related questions.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/zinamoukheiber/2010/11/16/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-sharecare/ |title=Names You Need To Know In 2011: Sharecare |magazine=Forbes.com |date= November 16, 2010 |access-date= April 1, 2011 |first=Zina |last=Moukheiber}}</ref>\n\nOz has been a professor at the Department of Surgery at [[Columbia University]] since 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asp.cumc.columbia.edu/facdb/profile_list.asp?uni=mco2&DepAffil=Surgery |title=Mehmet C. Oz, MD, FACS \u2013 Department of Surgery |publisher=Columbia University |date= |access-date= September 16, 2011}}</ref> He directs the Cardiovascular Institute and Complementary Medicine Program at [[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigthink.com/mehmetoz |title=Mehmet Oz &#124; Professor, Columbia University |publisher=Big Think |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> His research interests include heart valve replacement surgery, minimally invasive cardiac surgery, and health care policy. On April 15, 2020 he went on Fox News and stated schools should reopen because \"only\" 2-3% of students would die.\n\n===Television===\n{{Prose|section|date=February 2019}}\nOz appeared as a health expert on ''The Oprah Winfrey Show'' for five seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/contributor/dr-mehmet-oz |title=Live your best Life |publisher=Oprah.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Winfrey offered to produce a syndicated series hosted by him through her company, [[Harpo Productions]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> ''The Dr. Oz Show'' debuted September 14, 2009, distributed by Sony Pictures Television.\n\nOn the show, Oz addressed issues like Type 2 [[diabetes]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2010-02-04-Oprahdiabetes04_ST_N.htm|work=USA Today|title=Oprah Winfrey takes on a killer: type 2 diabetes|date= February 4, 2010|access-date= January 12, 2011}}</ref> and promoted [[resveratrol]] supplements, which he stated were anti-aging.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/06/15/mehmet-oz-oprah-business-media-resveratrol.html|first=Dirk|last=Smillie|work=Forbes|title=A Headache For Dr. Oz|date=16 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619083439/http://www.forbes.com/2009/06/15/mehmet-oz-oprah-business-media-resveratrol.html|archive-date= June 19, 2009}}</ref> His ''Transplant!'' television series won both a Freddie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreddies.com/Awards/Results.aspx?CategoryId=17&Year=2006 |title=The FREDDIE Awards |publisher=Thefreddies.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> and a Silver Telly award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tellyawards.com/winners/list/?l=L&event=7&category=1&award=S |title=The 31st Annual TELLY Awards &#124; Winners |publisher= TellyAwards.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> He served as medical director for [[Denzel Washington]]'s ''[[John Q]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0251160/fullcredits#cast |title=John Q (2002) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew | website = [[Internet Movie Database]] |year=2015 |access-date= February 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Oz premiered as part of a weekly show on [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]] called \"Oprah's Allstars\". In each episode, he, [[Suze Orman]], and [[Dr. Phil]] answer various questions about life, health and finance. He also currently does a health segment on [[1010 WINS]] titled \"Your Daily Dose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rbr.com/westwood-one-brings-dr-oz-to-wins-am-new-york/|title=Westwood One brings Dr. Oz to WINS-AM New York {{!}} Radio & Television Business Report|last=cmarcucci|website=rbr.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-08|date=November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2014, ''Surgeon Oz'', showing Oz's career as a surgeon, debuted on OWN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://decoy.tvpassport.com/news/dealing-demons-comic-book-renaissance-continues-nbc?subid=national-00001|title=Dealing with demons: Comic book renaissance|last=Warren|first=Andrew|publisher=TV Media}}</ref>\n\n====Television shows====\n*''Second Opinion with Dr Oz'' on [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] during the 2003\u201304 season <ref name=tvguide>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/mehmet-oz/bio/215510 |title=Mehmet Oz Biography |work=[[TV Guide]] |access-date= May 1, 2010}}</ref>\n*''Life Line'' on Discovery Health\n*''Daily Rounds'' on Discovery Health\n*''The Truth About Food'' on Discovery Health\n*''Live Transplant'' on Discovery Health\n*''National Body Challenge'' on Discovery Health\n*''You: On a Diet'' on Discovery Health\n*''Ask Dr. Oz'' on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]\n*''[[AccentHealth]]'' on Turner Private Networks\u2014a health-themed [[newsmagazine]] program designed for viewing in doctor's offices\n*''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'', Syndicated\n*''Your Life A to Z with Dr. Oz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azfamily.com/on-tv/your-life/Dr-Oz-Cooking-for-your-health-142214275.html |title=Dr. Oz: Cooking for your health}}</ref>\n*''[[NY Med]]'' on ABC\n*[[Dr. Ken]] on ABC (January 11, 2016)\n\n===Writing===\nEight of Oz's books have been ''New York Times'' bestsellers, of which seven were co-authored by [[Michael F. Roizen]]. He has a regular column in ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine and ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine]]'' and his article \"Retool, Reboot, and Rebuild\" was awarded the 2009 National Magazine Award for Personal Service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.magazine.org/asme/magazine_awards/nma_winners |title=American Society of Magazine Editors \u2013 2010 National Magazine Awards Winners Announced! |publisher=Magazine.org |date=April 22, 2010 |access-date=May 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109010249/http://www.magazine.org/asme/magazine_awards/nma_winners/ |archive-date=November 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Oz and the [[Hearst Corporation]] launched the bi-monthly magazine ''Dr. Oz THE GOOD LIFE'' on February 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/01/26/dr-oz-magazine-launch-set-for-feb-4/ |title=Dr. Oz magazine launch set for Feb. 4 | work =[[New York Post]] |date= January 26, 2014 |access-date= April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n*''Healing from the Heart: A Leading Surgeon Combines Eastern and Western Traditions to Create the Medicine of the Future'', by Mehmet \u00d6z, [[Ron Arias]], [[Dean Ornish]], 1999, {{ISBN|0-452-27955-0}}.\n*''Complementary and Alternative Cardiovascular Medicine: Clinical Handbook'', by Richard A. Stein (Editor), Mehmet, M.D. Oz (Editor), 2004, {{ISBN|1-58829-186-3}}.\n*''YOU: The Owner's Manual: An Insider's Guide to the Body that Will Make You Healthier and Younger'', by [[Michael F. Roizen]], Mehmet C. Oz, 2005, {{ISBN|0-06-076531-3}}.\n*''YOU: On a Diet: The Owner's Manual for Waist Management'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2006, {{ISBN|0-7432-9254-5}}.\n*''YOU: The Smart Patient: An Insider's Handbook for Getting the Best Treatment'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2006, {{ISBN|0-7432-9301-0}}.\n*''YOU: Staying Young: The Owner's Manual for Extending Your Warranty'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2007, {{ISBN|0-7432-9256-1}}.\n*''YOU: Being Beautiful: The Owner's Manual to Inner and Outer Beauty'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2008, {{ISBN|1-4165-7234-1}}.\n*''YOU: Breathing Easy: Meditation and Breathing Techniques to Help You Relax, Refresh, and Revitalize'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2008.\n*''YOU: Having a Baby: The Owner's Manual from Conception to Delivery and More'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2009.\n*''Minimally Invasive Cardiac Surgery'', by Mehmet C. Oz, 2010, {{ISBN|1-61737-400-8}}.\n*{{Cite book |title=Food Can Fix It: The Superfood Switch to Fight Fat, Defy Aging, and Eat Your Way Healthy |last=Oz |first=Mehmet |isbn=9781501158155 |location=New York|date=2017-09-26 }}\n*{{Cite book |title=YOU(R) Teen: Losing Weight: The Owner's Manual to Simple and Healthy Weight Management at Any Age |last1=Roizen |first1=Michael F. |last2=Oz |first2=Mehmet |date=2013 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=9781476713571 |edition=1st Free Press trade paperback |location=New York, NY |url=https://archive.org/details/yourteenlosingwe0000roiz }}\n*{{Cite book |title=YOU: The Owner's Manual for Teens: A Guide to a Healthy Body and Happy Life |last1=Roizen |first1=Michael F. |last2=Oz |first2=Mehmet |date=2011 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=9780743292580 |edition= 1st Free Press hardcover |location=New York}}\n\n==Controversies and criticism==\n{{Main|Medical claims on The Dr. Oz Show}}\nOz has faced criticism due to his tendency to feature non-scientific and [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] advice. He has been supportive of [[homeopathy]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.doctoroz.com/videos/homeopathy-starter-kit-pt-1 | title=Homeopathy Starter Kit, Pt 1 |work=[[The Dr. Oz Show]] | date=January 28, 2013 | access-date=May 22, 2014 }}</ref> and is a proponent of [[alternative medicine]].<ref name=\"ScamHearing\" />\n\nOz is a spokesman and advisor for the website [[RealAge]].com, which ''[[The New York Times]]'' has criticized for its pharmaceutical marketing practices.<ref name=\"Stephanie Clifford\">{{cite news |title=Online Age Quiz Is a Window for Drug Makers |author=Stephanie Clifford |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/26/technology/internet/26privacy.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date=March 25, 2009 |access-date=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis image and quotes have been exploited by many weight loss product\u00a0[[scam]]mers. While he himself has not been found to be involved in these scams, he has made statements that were exploited by scammers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/06/17/dr-oz-gets-scolded-by-senators-over-weight-loss-scams/ |title=Dr. Oz gets scolded by senators over weight loss scams |publisher = [[Fox News]] |date=June 17, 2014 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Stephanie Clifford\"/> During a Senate hearing on consumer protection, Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] stated that \"the scientific community is almost monolithic against you\" for airing segments on weight loss products that are later cited in advertisements, concluding that Oz plays a role, intentional or not, in perpetuating these scams, and that she is \"concerned that you are melding medical advice, news, and entertainment in a way that harms consumers.\"<ref name=\"USATodayMcCaskill\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/06/17/dr-oz-senate-panel-weight-scams/10701067/ |title=Senators scold Dr. Oz for weight-loss scams |last=Mutnick |first=Ally |date=2014-06-17 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=ScamHearing>{{cite web |title=Senate Sub-Committee for Commerce, Science, and Transportation Hearing on Protecting Consumers from False and Deceptive Advertising of Weight-Loss Products |url=http://www.commerce.senate.gov/public/index.cfm?p=Hearings&ContentRecord_id=c1698871-3625-4f67-b0e5-a06d3bab6ca1&ContentType_id=14f995b9-dfa5-407a-9d35-56cc7152a7ed&Group_id=02096e14-bdcc-424b-842c-d6809f3f69c9 |date=June 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, during his [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]], Donald Trump appeared on ''The Dr. Oz Show''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/donald-trump-tapes-dr-oz-physical-exam-results-1201819504/|title=Donald Trump Plays Media With \"Surprise\" Handover Of Physical Exam Rundown At 'Dr. Oz' Taping|magazine=Deadline|first1=Lisa|last1=de Moraes|date=September 14, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> In the lead-up to the show's taping, Oz promoted Trump's appearance with a claim that Oz would assess medical records submitted to the show by Trump and reveal his assessment on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/dr-oz-trump-medical-records-228089#ixzz4KFueVKZq|title=Dr. Oz pledges to avoid questions Trump 'doesn't want to have answered'|publisher=Politico|first1=Nick|last1=Gass|date=September 9, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Several news outlets speculated that Trump's appearance aimed to appeal to ''The Dr. Oz Show's'' large female viewership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/09/16/opinions/trump-clinton-health-war-vox-opinion/index.html|title=Trump and Oz: A match made in tv heaven|publisher=CNN|first1=Ford|last1=Vox|date=September 18, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/09/14/media/dr-oz-donald-trump-taping/index.html|title=Donald Trump surprises Dr. Oz with results of recent physical|publisher=CNN|first1=Brian|last1=Stetler|first2=MJ|last2=Lee|date=September 14, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Trump appointed Oz, athletes and ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' star [[Lou Ferrigno]] to his Council on Sports, Fitness, and Nutrition. Trump's selections were criticized as choosing \"pundits over experts\" for the panel.<ref name=intelligencer>{{Cite web |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/05/trump-appoints-incredible-hulk-and-dr-oz-to-sports-panel.html |title=Trump Appoints Incredible Hulk, Athletes, and Dr. Oz to Sports Panel |last=Raymond |first=Adam K. |date=2018-05-04 |website=Intelligencer |language=en |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n===Lack of scientific validity===\n[[File:McCaskill Takes Aim at Diet Scams That Are 'A Crisis in Consumer Protection'.webm|thumb|right|Oz was heavily criticised by Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] in a hearing on consumer fraud in diet product advertising.]]\n''[[Popular Science]]''<ref name=\"PopSci\">{{cite web |url=http://www.popsci.com/science/article/2013-01/dr-oz-bad-science |title=Is Dr. Oz Bad For Science? |work=[[Popular Science]] |date=January 30, 2013 |access-date=March 11, 2014 |author=Lecher, Colin}}</ref> and ''[[The New Yorker]]''<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2013/02/04/130204fa_fact_specter |title=The Operator |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=February 4, 2013 |access-date=March 11, 2014 |author=Specter, Michael|author-link=Michael Specter}}</ref> have published critical articles on Oz for giving \"non-scientific\" advice and questioning if he is \"doing more harm than good\"<ref name=\"NewYorker\" />\n\nThe [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] has awarded Oz with their [[Pigasus Award]], an award intended \"to expose parapsychological, paranormal or psychic frauds that Randi has noted over the previous year.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/component/content/article/37-static/256-pigasus-awards.html |title=Pigasus Awards |first=Jeff |last=Wagg |publisher=James Randi Educational Foundation |date=October 31, 2008 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2009, Oz received the award for the promotion of energy therapies such as [[Reiki]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pigasus Awards |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/swift-blog/928-the-2009-pigasus-awards.html |publisher=James Randi Education Foundation |date=April 2, 2010 |access-date= October 14, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Oz received the award for support of [[faith healing]] and [[mediumship|psychic communication with the dead]], among other controversial practices. Oz became the first person to receive a Pigasus Award two years in a row.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/health/boostershots/la-heb-dr-oz-andrew-wakefield-james-randi-awards-20110401,0,3573991.story |title=Dr. Oz, Andrew Wakefield and others, um, 'honored' by James Randi |access-date=April 2, 2011 |author=Mestel, Rosie |date=April 1, 2011 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In 2012, Oz won \"The Pigasus Award for Refusal to Face Reality\" for his continued promotion of \"quack medical practices, paranormal belief, and pseudoscience\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Randi|first1=James|authorlink=James Randi|title=JREF's Pigasus Awards \"Honors\" Dubious Peddlers of \"Woo\" |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/jref-news/2074-jrefs-pigasus-awards-honors-dubious-peddlers-of-woo.html |publisher=James Randi Education Foundation |date=April 1, 2013 |access-date= October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 study published in the ''British Medical Journal'' found that medical talk shows such as ''The Dr Oz Show'' and ''The Doctors'' often lack adequate information on the specific benefits or evidence of their claims. 40 episodes of each program from early 2013 were evaluated, determining that evidence supported 46 percent, contradicted 15 percent and was not found for 39 percent of the recommendations on ''The Dr Oz Show''.<ref name=fast/><ref name=\"mehmetpost\">{{cite journal|last1=Korownyk |first1=Christina |title=Televised medical talk shows\u2014what they recommend and the evidence to support their recommendations: a prospective observational study |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g7346 |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=349 |pages=g7346 |doi=10.1136/bmj.g7346 |pmid=25520234 |date= December 17, 2014|pmc=4269523}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, a group of ten physicians from prestigious institutions called for Columbia University to part ways with Oz, who was the vice chair of the Department of Surgery. More than 1,300 doctors signed a letter sent to the university.<ref name=fast/><ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2015/04/17/health/dr-oz-columbia-letter/ \"Physicians to Columbia University: 'Dismayed' that Dr. Oz is on faculty\"]. [[CNN]]. April 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Viewpoints==\n===Medical marijuana===\nOz denounced the \"hypocrisy\" in the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]]'s classification of [[cannabis]] as a Schedule I, controlled substance on ''[[Fox & Friends]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.leafly.com/news/podcasts/podcast-the-roll-up-3-dr-oz-and-fox-friends |title=The Roll-Up #3: Dr. Oz and Fox & Friends |date=2017-09-22 |website=Leafly |language=en-US |access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> He has advocated for medical marijuana as a solution for the [[opioid epidemic]] during an episode of the series featuring [[Montel Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefix.com/dr-oz-and-montel-williams-whether-marijuana-can-treat-opioid-addiction |title=Dr. Oz and Montel Williams on Whether Marijuana Can Treat Opioid Addiction |date=2017-09-22 |website=The Fix |language=en |access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n===Backpage===\nOz has voiced his support of shutting down [[Backpage]], a controversial website which was seized by U.S. authorities in April 2018. Backpage has earned millions of dollars by allowing sex ads to be hosted on its website, some of which featured children. The site has been supported by the [[Center for Democracy and Technology]] and the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/opinion/outlook/article/Mazzio-Oz-Kids-are-no-match-for-Backpage-11107837.php|title=Mazzio, Oz: Kids are no match for 'Backpage'|last1=Mazzio|first1=Mary|last2=Oz|first2=Mehmet|date=April 28, 2017|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/siriusxmentertainment/dr-oz-shutting-down-backpagecom|title=Dr. Oz: Shutting Down Backpage|last1=Oz|first1=Mehmet|publisher=SiriusXM Entertainment|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> The [[Stop Enabling Sex Traffickers Act]] (SESTA) and the Allow States and Victims to Fight Online Sex Trafficking Act (FOSTA) have been passed by the [[U.S. Congress]] in 2018 as a response to Backpage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/01/10/backpage-com-shuts-down-adult-services-ads-after-relentless-pressure-from-authorities|title=Backpage.com shuts down adult services ads after relentless pressure from authorities|last1=Hawkins|first1=Derek|date=January 10, 2017|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Lisa Oz Mehmet Oz David Shankbone 2010.jpg|thumb|Oz and his wife Lisa]]\nOz lives in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey|Cliffside Park]], [[New Jersey]], with his wife [[Lisa Oz|Lisa]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Bruni, Frank | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/18/magazine/18Oz-t.html |title=Dr. Does-It-All |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 16, 2010 |access-date=March 22, 2011 |quote=That is his base line, to which he adds more yoga, short runs and basketball games with friends near his home in Cliffside Park, N.J., when he can.| author-link=Frank Bruni }}</ref> They have been married since 1985<ref>Married on July 29, 1985 in Bryn Athyn, PA \u2013 ''New Church Life'', 1985, p. 430.</ref> and have four children and four grandchildren.<ref>[https://people.com/parents/daphne-oz-welcomes-daughter-giovanna-ines-exclusive/ (August 15, 2019). Baby Makes Six! Daphne Oz Welcomes Daughter Giovanna Ines. People Magazine.]</ref> His eldest daughter is author and television host [[Daphne Oz]]. Oz and his wife founded [[HealthCorps]], a [[non-profit organization]] for [[health]] [[education]] and [[peer mentoring]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.success.com/how-dr-oz-healthcorps-is-creating-young-leaders/ |title=How Dr. Oz's HealthCorps Is Creating Young Leaders |date=2018-10-05 |website=SUCCESS |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nOz is fluent in English and [[Turkish Language|Turkish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkturkey.us/2009/07/the-wizard-of-dr-oz.html |title=The Wizard of Dr Oz \u2013 talkturkey |publisher=Talkturkey.us |date= July 19, 2009 |access-date= May 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520011523/http://www.talkturkey.us/2009/07/the-wizard-of-dr-oz.html |archive-date=May 20, 2010 }}</ref> He is a holder of [[Turkish nationality law|Turkish]] and American citizenship, having served in the [[Turkish Army]] to retain his Turkish citizenship.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/30/magazine/the-experiments-of-dr-oz.html?pagewanted=3 | work= [[The New York Times]] | title=The Experiments of Dr. Oz | first=Chip | last=Brown | date= July 30, 1995 | access-date= May 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOz grew up in a mixed [[Muslim]] environment where his father's family practiced more traditional [[Islam]], while his mother's family were more [[secular]] Muslims.<ref>{{cite video |people=Dr. Oz |year= 2010|title=Islam and Identity |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/video/islam-and-identity/140/ |format=Flash Video |medium= |trans_title= |publisher=PBS |location= |access-date= April 22, 2010}}</ref> Oz identifies himself as a Muslim<ref name=\"Business Insider\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/these-9-famous-americans-are-all-muslim-2014-10|title=9 Famous Americans You Probably Didn't Know Were Muslim |publisher=businessinsider.com |date= October 27, 2014 |access-date= April 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"wfaa8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/health/2014/08/10/13618098/ |title=Dr. Oz: The inside story |publisher=[[WFAA|WFAA.com]] |date=August 10, 2014 |access-date=April 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120093330/http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/health/2014/08/10/13618098/ |archive-date=January 20, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and says that he has been influenced by the mysticism of [[Sufi]] Muslims from Central Turkey,<ref name=\"theroot1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theroot.com/multimedia/meet-faces-america-dr-mehmet-oz |title=Henry Louis Gates Jr. Faces of America: Dr. Mehmet Oz |publisher=Theroot.com |date=August 19, 2010 |access-date=August 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424075849/http://www.theroot.com/multimedia/meet-faces-america-dr-mehmet-oz |archive-date=April 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as the ideas of [[Emanuel Swedenborg]], the 18th-century Swedish theologian, scientist, philosopher, revelator and mystic.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Martin Gardner |last=Gardner |first=Martin |year=2010 |title=Swedenborg and Dr. Oz. |journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |volume=34 |number=5 |url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/swedenborg_and_dr._oz/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spirituality-health.com/NMagazine/articles.php?id=1768 |title=Spirituality & Health: Mehmet Oz Finds His Teacher |publisher=Spirituality-health.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOz is a practitioner of [[Transcendental Meditation technique|transcendental meditation]]. \"When I meditate, I go to that place where truth lives,\" he said. \"I can see what reality really is, and it is so much easier to form good relationships then.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/features/tribu/ct-tribu-skube-multitasking,0,5213589.column | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Become a wizard of multitasking! | first=Daneen | last=Skube}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Oz was diagnosed with a pre-cancerous [[Polyp (medicine)|polyp]] in the colon during a routine [[colonoscopy]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2010/09/dr-oz-high-risk-after-cancer-scare/1 | work=USAToday.com | title=Dr. Oz 'high risk' after cancer scare | date= September 1, 2010 | access-date= October 18, 2010}}</ref> which was performed as part of his show. Oz said that the procedure likely saved his life.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20417551,00.html |work=People |title=Dr. Oz Has Colon Cancer Scare |first=Charlotte |last=Triggs |date= September 1, 2010| access-date= November 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Oz played for the \"Home\" roster during the [[2019 NBA All-Star Game#Celebrity Game|NBA All-Star Celebrity Game]] at the [[Bojangles' Coliseum]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]. The roster was made up of celebrities with Carolina roots.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/article/2019/02/06/2019-celebrity-game-participants-official-release |title=ESPN and NBA announce celebrity rosters and coaches for 2019 NBA All-Star Celebrity Game presented by Ruffles exclusively on ESPN |last=release |first=Official |website=NBA.com |language=en |access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> He previously played in the [[2010 NBA All-Star Game#Celebrity Game|NBA All-Star Celebrity Game]].<ref name=\"charlotte\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.valdostadailytimes.com/news/lifestyles/he-ll-be-the-oldest-player-in-the-nba-all/article_5b6c62ab-fce7-5a1b-9234-cdc8b804a1a5.html |title=He'll be the oldest player in the NBA All-Star Celebrity Game. Why is Dr. Oz doing this? |last=Janes |first=Th\u00e9oden   |website=The Charlotte Observer |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Also in 2019, Oz played for Team Cleveland in [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[All-Star Legends & Celebrity Softball Game]] at [[Progressive Field]] in Cleveland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Dan |title=MLB All-Star celebrity softball game 2019: Roster boasts famous names, former athletes, J.R. Smith |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/mlb-celebrity-softball-game-2019-full-roster-boasts-famous-names-former-athletes-jr-smith/86olgiinxyhz1rhb1ji30yupe |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=July 8, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999-2004, Oz was named a \"Global Leader of Tomorrow\" by the [[World Economic Forum]]<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/profiles/dr-mehmet-oz/4/</ref> and was listed on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine's]]'' \"100 Most Influential People\" of 2008.<ref>http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1733748_1733754_1735329,00.html</ref> He has been nominated for nine [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host|Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Talk Show Host]] since ''The Dr. Oz Show'' premiered in 2009, and won the award in 2010, 2011, 2014 and 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2016/05/02/General-Hospital-Live-with-Kelly-Michael-win-big-at-the-Daytime-Emmy-Awards/2271462123287/|date=May 2, 2016|title='General Hospital,' 'Live with Kelly & Michael' win big at the Daytime Emmy Awards|author=Butler, Karen| publisher = [[United Press International]] |access-date=May 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2014/06/22/daytime-emmys-2014-winners/ |title=Daytime Emmys: Y&R Dominates Soap Pack; AMC and OLTL Get 3 Wins Each |last=Mitovich |first=Matt Webb |last2=Mitovich |first2=Matt Webb |date=2014-06-23 |website=TVLine |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2011/06/2011-daytime-emmy-award-winners-141381/ |title=2011 Daytime Emmy Award Winners |last=Team |first=The Deadline |last2=Team |first2=The Deadline |date=2011-06-20 |website=Deadline |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2010/06/2010-daytime-emmy-winners-as-the-world-turns-bold-beautiful-cash-cab-and-dr-oz-49888/ |title=2010 Daytime Emmy Winners: 'As The World Turns', 'Bold & Beautiful', 'Young & Restless', 'General Hospital', 'Cash Cab', 'Ellen', 'Dr Oz', And 'The Doctors' |last=Finke |first=Nikki |last2=Finke |first2=Nikki |date=2010-06-28 |website=Deadline |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Medical journalism]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last=Brown |first=Heidi |url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/08/04/oprah-health-doctor-forbeslife-cx_hb_0804oz.html |title=Oprah Loves This Doctor |journal=[[Forbes|Forbes Magazine]] |date=August 4, 2008 |access-date=June 1, 2015}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Specter |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Specter |date=February 4, 2013 |title=The operator : is the most trusted doctor in America doing more harm than good? |department=Profiles |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=88 |issue=46 |pages=40\u201349 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/02/04/the-operator |access-date=January 9, 2015}}\n* {{Cite news |last=Gladstone |first=Brooke |author-link=Brooke Gladstone |title=Dr. Oz Fights for Credibility |url=http://www.onthemedia.org/story/dr-oz-fights-credibility/ |work=[[On the Media]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=April 24, 2015 |access-date=June 1, 2015}} Discussion with Michael Specter about his profile of Oz.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mehmet Oz}}\n* [http://columbiasurgery.org/mehmet-c-oz-md-facs Columbia University Department of Surgery profile]\n* {{IMDb name|1185906}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Mehmet Oz\n| list =\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Host}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Informative Talk Show Host}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oz, Mehmet}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American cardiac surgeons]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American health and wellness writers]]\n[[Category:American health care businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American magazine writers]]\n[[Category:American medical writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Circassian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Celebrity doctors]]\n[[Category:Citizens of Turkey through descent]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Esquire (magazine)]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medical educators]]\n[[Category:NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital physicians]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:People from Cliffside Park, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Shapsugs]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Turkish people of Circassian descent]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wilmington, Delaware]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Tower Hill School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Dr. Oz|the syndicated talk series|The Dr. Oz Show}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mehmet \u00d6z\n| image       = Mehmet Oz official photo.jpg\n| birth_name = Mehmet Cengiz \u00d6z\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Talk show host, surgeon,  author\n| children = 4, including [[Daphne Oz]]\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Lisa Oz|Lisa Lemole]]|1985}}\n| years_active = 1982\u2013present\n| education  = [[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] {{small|([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}\n| website  = {{url|doctoroz.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Mehmet Cengiz \u00d6z''' ({{IPA-tr|meh\u02c8met d\u0292e\u0272\u02c8\u025fiz \u0153z|lang}}; born June 11, 1960),<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web| url=https://www.biography.com/personality/dr-oz|title=Dr. Oz (1960\u2013)|publisher=[[Biography.com]]|accessdate= October 13, 2019|archivedate=June 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190612173946/https://www.biography.com/personality/dr-oz|url-status=live}}</ref> known professionally as '''Dr. Oz''', is a [[Turkish Americans|Turkish American]]<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1688472/Mehmet-Oz |title=Mehmet Oz biography \u2013 Turkish American surgeon, educator, and author |first=Amy |last=Tikkanen |encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |year=2015 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> [[television personality]], [[cardiothoracic surgeon]], [[Columbia University]] professor,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://columbiasurgery.org/mehmet-c-oz-md-facs|title=Mehmet C. Oz, MD, FACS {{!}} Columbia University Department of Surgery|website=columbiasurgery.org|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> [[pseudoscience]] promoter,<ref name=\"Salon2015\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.salon.com/2015/04/17/physicians_urge_columbia_to_drop_its_unacceptable_affiliation_with_pseudoscience_promoter_dr_oz/|title=Physicians urge Columbia to drop its \"unacceptable\" affiliation with pseudoscience promoter Dr. Oz|last=Abrams|first=Lindsay|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=2017-06-19|date=2015-04-17}}</ref> journalist, and [[author]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsmax.com/FastFeatures/Green-Coffee-Beans-Extract-Reviews-Congress-Investigation-Supplements/2015/03/16/id/630396/|title=Green Coffee Beans Extract Reviews: What Congress Found In Its Investigation|work=Newsmax|access-date=2017-06-19}}</ref> In 2003, [[Oprah Winfrey]] was the first guest on the [[Discovery Channel]] series ''Second Opinion with Dr. Oz'',<ref name=oprah>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oprah.com/health/dr-oz-and-oprah-interview-how-to-find-balance-in-your-life/all |title=Dr. Oz Talks to Oprah About Food, Family and What It Really Means to Be Healthy |publisher=Oprah.com |language=en-us |access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> and, since 2004, Oz became a regular guest on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', making more than sixty appearances.<ref name=oprah/> In 2009, ''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'', a daily television program focusing on medical issues and personal health, was launched by Winfrey's [[Harpo Productions]] and [[Sony Pictures Television]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/pressroom/pressrelease/20080613_orig_drozsony|title=Harpo Productions and Sony Pictures Television To Launch Dr. Oz|work=Oprah.com|date=June 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe is a proponent of [[alternative medicine]], and has been criticized by physicians, government officials, and publications, including ''[[Popular Science]]'' and ''[[The New Yorker]]'', for endorsing unproven products and non-scientific advice. The ''[[British Medical Journal]]'' published a study that found more than half of the recommendations on medical talk series like ''The Dr. Oz Show'' had either no evidence or contradicted medical research.<ref name=\"mehmetpost\" />  [[Donald Trump]]'s appointment of Oz to the Council on Sports, Fitness, and Nutrition was criticized as an example of choosing \"pundits over experts\".<ref name=intelligencer /><ref name=fast>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40568706/heres-why-dr-oz-is-an-absurd-choice-for-trumps-health-council |title=Here's Why Dr. Oz Is An Absurd Choice For Trump's Health Council |last=Raphael |first=Rina |date=2018-05-07 |website=Fast Company |language=en-US |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nOz was born in 1960 in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], to Suna and Mustafa \u00d6z, who had emigrated from [[Konya Province]], [[Turkey]].<ref name=gma20090831>{{cite news|first=Lana|last=Zak|title=Dr. Oz on Complementary Medicine: 'Challenge the Status Quo'|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/OnCall/story?id=8450292|work=Good Morning America|date = August 31, 2009|access-date= October 12, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Faces\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/profiles/dr-mehmet-oz/4/ |title=Faces of America: Dr. Mehmet Oz |work=[[Faces of America (PBS series)|Faces of America]]'' series, with Professor [[Henry Louis Gates|Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] |year=2010}}</ref> Mustafa, born in [[Bozk\u0131r]], a small town in southern Turkey, earned scholarships that allowed him to emigrate to the United States as a [[Residency (medicine)|medical resident]] in 1955. Suna (n\u00e9e Atabay), who comes from a wealthy [[Istanbul]] family, is the daughter of a [[pharmacist]] with [[Circassians|Circassian]] ([[Shapsug]]) descent on her mother's side. Oz has two sisters, Seval \u00d6z and Nazlim \u00d6z.<ref name=\"Faces\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Dr. Mehmet \u00d6z'\u00fcn D\u00fczce'ye uzanan soya\u011fac\u0131 |url=http://jinepsgazetesi.com/index.php?module=news&news_id=11655&cat_id=106 |work=Jineps |date= January 1, 2011 |access-date= September 17, 2011 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\nOz was educated at [[Tower Hill School]] in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]].<ref name=\"PhillyInterview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/exit-interview-dr-oz/ | title=Exit Interview: Dr. Oz | publisher=[[Metrocorp]] | work=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia]] | date=October 30, 2009 | access-date=March 11, 2014 | last=Rys |first=Richard}}</ref> In 1982, he received his undergraduate degree in biology at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=7641721&privcapId=79086309&previousCapId=29249600&previousTitle=The%20Cue%20Ball%20Group,%20LLC|work=Business Week |title= Executive Profile: Mehmet C. Oz M.D |access-date=January 12, 2011}}</ref> He played safety on Harvard's football team and won an intramural college championship playing water polo.<ref name=\"charlotte\"/> In 1986, he obtained [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] and [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] degrees, respectively, at the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]]<ref name=\"PhillyInterview\"/> and Penn's [[Wharton School]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Lizzy |last=Ratner |title=The Great and Powerful Dr. Oz |url=http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/great-and-powerful-dr-oz |work=[[New York Observer]] |date= August 14, 2007 |access-date= September 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020021729/http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/great-and-powerful-dr-oz |archive-date=October 20, 2007 }}</ref> He was awarded the Captain's Athletic Award for leadership in college<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.abc.daytonsnewssource.com/sections/entertainment/droz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704070306/http://abc.daytonsnewssource.com/sections/entertainment/droz/ | year=2010| publisher= WKEF-TV |archive-date= July 4, 2010 | title= Mehmet C. Oz, M.D.}}</ref> and was [[class president]] and then [[student body president]] during medical school.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.talkshows.about.com/od/thedrozshow/p/DrOzBio.htm |title= Dr Oz \u2013 The Dr Oz Show |publisher= about.com |access-date= May 22, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160120093331/http://talkshows.about.com/od/thedrozshow/p/DrOzBio.htm |archive-date= January 20, 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dr. Oz at ServiceNation 2008.jpg|thumb|Mehmet Oz at [[ServiceNation]] in 2008]]\n\n===Medical===\nIn 1996, Ottavio Alfieri proposed to Oz that the mitral valve only needed one suture to close a leak. He developed the idea to use a catheter to put one staple in and submitted the patent for [[MitraClip]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/703961/ccopelan/how-dr-oz-kick-started-a-groundbreaking-device-for-patients-with-heart-failure/|title=How Dr. Oz Kick-Started a Groundbreaking Device for Patients with Heart Failure|author=Copelan, Christine|date=26 September 2018|work=Parade}}</ref> In the late 1990s, Oz began recommending [[ventricular assist device]]s as an alternative for patients with heart failure.<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/eheart/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Oz joined [[Jeff Arnold (Internet entrepreneur)|Jeff Arnold]] as co-founder of [[Sharecare|Sharecare, Inc.]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health2con.com/news/2010/10/18/san-francisco-2010-launch-of-sharecare/ |title=Sharecare, Inc. |publisher=Health 2.0 |access-date=March 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208104438/http://www.health2con.com/news/2010/10/18/san-francisco-2010-launch-of-sharecare/ |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> providing an interactive question and answer platform for industry experts to answer health-related questions.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/zinamoukheiber/2010/11/16/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-sharecare/ |title=Names You Need To Know In 2011: Sharecare |magazine=Forbes.com |date= November 16, 2010 |access-date= April 1, 2011 |first=Zina |last=Moukheiber}}</ref>\n\nOz has been a professor at the Department of Surgery at [[Columbia University]] since 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asp.cumc.columbia.edu/facdb/profile_list.asp?uni=mco2&DepAffil=Surgery |title=Mehmet C. Oz, MD, FACS \u2013 Department of Surgery |publisher=Columbia University |date= |access-date= September 16, 2011}}</ref> He directs the Cardiovascular Institute and Complementary Medicine Program at [[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigthink.com/mehmetoz |title=Mehmet Oz &#124; Professor, Columbia University |publisher=Big Think |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> His research interests include heart valve replacement surgery, minimally invasive cardiac surgery, and health care policy. On April 15, 2020 he went on Fox News and stated schools should reopen because \"only\" 2-3% of students would die.\n\n===Television===\n{{Prose|section|date=February 2019}}\nOz appeared as a health expert on ''The Oprah Winfrey Show'' for five seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/contributor/dr-mehmet-oz |title=Live your best Life |publisher=Oprah.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Winfrey offered to produce a syndicated series hosted by him through her company, [[Harpo Productions]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> ''The Dr. Oz Show'' debuted September 14, 2009, distributed by Sony Pictures Television.\n\nOn the show, Oz addressed issues like Type 2 [[diabetes]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2010-02-04-Oprahdiabetes04_ST_N.htm|work=USA Today|title=Oprah Winfrey takes on a killer: type 2 diabetes|date= February 4, 2010|access-date= January 12, 2011}}</ref> and promoted [[resveratrol]] supplements, which he stated were anti-aging.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/06/15/mehmet-oz-oprah-business-media-resveratrol.html|first=Dirk|last=Smillie|work=Forbes|title=A Headache For Dr. Oz|date=16 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619083439/http://www.forbes.com/2009/06/15/mehmet-oz-oprah-business-media-resveratrol.html|archive-date= June 19, 2009}}</ref> His ''Transplant!'' television series won both a Freddie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreddies.com/Awards/Results.aspx?CategoryId=17&Year=2006 |title=The FREDDIE Awards |publisher=Thefreddies.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> and a Silver Telly award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tellyawards.com/winners/list/?l=L&event=7&category=1&award=S |title=The 31st Annual TELLY Awards &#124; Winners |publisher= TellyAwards.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref> He served as medical director for [[Denzel Washington]]'s ''[[John Q]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0251160/fullcredits#cast |title=John Q (2002) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew | website = [[Internet Movie Database]] |year=2015 |access-date= February 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Oz premiered as part of a weekly show on [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]] called \"Oprah's Allstars\". In each episode, he, [[Suze Orman]], and [[Dr. Phil]] answer various questions about life, health and finance. He also currently does a health segment on [[1010 WINS]] titled \"Your Daily Dose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rbr.com/westwood-one-brings-dr-oz-to-wins-am-new-york/|title=Westwood One brings Dr. Oz to WINS-AM New York {{!}} Radio & Television Business Report|last=cmarcucci|website=rbr.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-08|date=November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2014, ''Surgeon Oz'', showing Oz's career as a surgeon, debuted on OWN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://decoy.tvpassport.com/news/dealing-demons-comic-book-renaissance-continues-nbc?subid=national-00001|title=Dealing with demons: Comic book renaissance|last=Warren|first=Andrew|publisher=TV Media}}</ref>\n\n====Television shows====\n*''Second Opinion with Dr Oz'' on [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] during the 2003\u201304 season <ref name=tvguide>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/mehmet-oz/bio/215510 |title=Mehmet Oz Biography |work=[[TV Guide]] |access-date= May 1, 2010}}</ref>\n*''Life Line'' on Discovery Health\n*''Daily Rounds'' on Discovery Health\n*''The Truth About Food'' on Discovery Health\n*''Live Transplant'' on Discovery Health\n*''National Body Challenge'' on Discovery Health\n*''You: On a Diet'' on Discovery Health\n*''Ask Dr. Oz'' on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]\n*''[[AccentHealth]]'' on Turner Private Networks\u2014a health-themed [[newsmagazine]] program designed for viewing in doctor's offices\n*''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'', Syndicated\n*''Your Life A to Z with Dr. Oz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azfamily.com/on-tv/your-life/Dr-Oz-Cooking-for-your-health-142214275.html |title=Dr. Oz: Cooking for your health}}</ref>\n*''[[NY Med]]'' on ABC\n*[[Dr. Ken]] on ABC (January 11, 2016)\n\n===Writing===\nEight of Oz's books have been ''New York Times'' bestsellers, of which seven were co-authored by [[Michael F. Roizen]]. He has a regular column in ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine and ''[[O, The Oprah Magazine]]'' and his article \"Retool, Reboot, and Rebuild\" was awarded the 2009 National Magazine Award for Personal Service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.magazine.org/asme/magazine_awards/nma_winners |title=American Society of Magazine Editors \u2013 2010 National Magazine Awards Winners Announced! |publisher=Magazine.org |date=April 22, 2010 |access-date=May 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109010249/http://www.magazine.org/asme/magazine_awards/nma_winners/ |archive-date=November 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Oz and the [[Hearst Corporation]] launched the bi-monthly magazine ''Dr. Oz THE GOOD LIFE'' on February 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/01/26/dr-oz-magazine-launch-set-for-feb-4/ |title=Dr. Oz magazine launch set for Feb. 4 | work =[[New York Post]] |date= January 26, 2014 |access-date= April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n*''Healing from the Heart: A Leading Surgeon Combines Eastern and Western Traditions to Create the Medicine of the Future'', by Mehmet \u00d6z, [[Ron Arias]], [[Dean Ornish]], 1999, {{ISBN|0-452-27955-0}}.\n*''Complementary and Alternative Cardiovascular Medicine: Clinical Handbook'', by Richard A. Stein (Editor), Mehmet, M.D. Oz (Editor), 2004, {{ISBN|1-58829-186-3}}.\n*''YOU: The Owner's Manual: An Insider's Guide to the Body that Will Make You Healthier and Younger'', by [[Michael F. Roizen]], Mehmet C. Oz, 2005, {{ISBN|0-06-076531-3}}.\n*''YOU: On a Diet: The Owner's Manual for Waist Management'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2006, {{ISBN|0-7432-9254-5}}.\n*''YOU: The Smart Patient: An Insider's Handbook for Getting the Best Treatment'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2006, {{ISBN|0-7432-9301-0}}.\n*''YOU: Staying Young: The Owner's Manual for Extending Your Warranty'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2007, {{ISBN|0-7432-9256-1}}.\n*''YOU: Being Beautiful: The Owner's Manual to Inner and Outer Beauty'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2008, {{ISBN|1-4165-7234-1}}.\n*''YOU: Breathing Easy: Meditation and Breathing Techniques to Help You Relax, Refresh, and Revitalize'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2008.\n*''YOU: Having a Baby: The Owner's Manual from Conception to Delivery and More'', by Michael F. Roizen, Mehmet C. Oz, 2009.\n*''Minimally Invasive Cardiac Surgery'', by Mehmet C. Oz, 2010, {{ISBN|1-61737-400-8}}.\n*{{Cite book |title=Food Can Fix It: The Superfood Switch to Fight Fat, Defy Aging, and Eat Your Way Healthy |last=Oz |first=Mehmet |isbn=9781501158155 |location=New York|date=2017-09-26 }}\n*{{Cite book |title=YOU(R) Teen: Losing Weight: The Owner's Manual to Simple and Healthy Weight Management at Any Age |last1=Roizen |first1=Michael F. |last2=Oz |first2=Mehmet |date=2013 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=9781476713571 |edition=1st Free Press trade paperback |location=New York, NY |url=https://archive.org/details/yourteenlosingwe0000roiz }}\n*{{Cite book |title=YOU: The Owner's Manual for Teens: A Guide to a Healthy Body and Happy Life |last1=Roizen |first1=Michael F. |last2=Oz |first2=Mehmet |date=2011 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=9780743292580 |edition= 1st Free Press hardcover |location=New York}}\n\n==Controversies and criticism==\n{{Main|Medical claims on The Dr. Oz Show}}\nOz has faced criticism due to his tendency to feature non-scientific and [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] advice. He has been supportive of [[homeopathy]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.doctoroz.com/videos/homeopathy-starter-kit-pt-1 | title=Homeopathy Starter Kit, Pt 1 |work=[[The Dr. Oz Show]] | date=January 28, 2013 | access-date=May 22, 2014 }}</ref> and is a proponent of [[alternative medicine]].<ref name=\"ScamHearing\" />\n\nOz is a spokesman and advisor for the website [[RealAge]].com, which ''[[The New York Times]]'' has criticized for its pharmaceutical marketing practices.<ref name=\"Stephanie Clifford\">{{cite news |title=Online Age Quiz Is a Window for Drug Makers |author=Stephanie Clifford |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/26/technology/internet/26privacy.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date=March 25, 2009 |access-date=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis image and quotes have been exploited by many weight loss product\u00a0[[scam]]mers. While he himself has not been found to be involved in these scams, he has made statements that were exploited by scammers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/06/17/dr-oz-gets-scolded-by-senators-over-weight-loss-scams/ |title=Dr. Oz gets scolded by senators over weight loss scams |publisher = [[Fox News]] |date=June 17, 2014 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Stephanie Clifford\"/> During a Senate hearing on consumer protection, Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] stated that \"the scientific community is almost monolithic against you\" for airing segments on weight loss products that are later cited in advertisements, concluding that Oz plays a role, intentional or not, in perpetuating these scams, and that she is \"concerned that you are melding medical advice, news, and entertainment in a way that harms consumers.\"<ref name=\"USATodayMcCaskill\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/06/17/dr-oz-senate-panel-weight-scams/10701067/ |title=Senators scold Dr. Oz for weight-loss scams |last=Mutnick |first=Ally |date=2014-06-17 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=ScamHearing>{{cite web |title=Senate Sub-Committee for Commerce, Science, and Transportation Hearing on Protecting Consumers from False and Deceptive Advertising of Weight-Loss Products |url=http://www.commerce.senate.gov/public/index.cfm?p=Hearings&ContentRecord_id=c1698871-3625-4f67-b0e5-a06d3bab6ca1&ContentType_id=14f995b9-dfa5-407a-9d35-56cc7152a7ed&Group_id=02096e14-bdcc-424b-842c-d6809f3f69c9 |date=June 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, during his [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]], Donald Trump appeared on ''The Dr. Oz Show''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/donald-trump-tapes-dr-oz-physical-exam-results-1201819504/|title=Donald Trump Plays Media With \"Surprise\" Handover Of Physical Exam Rundown At 'Dr. Oz' Taping|magazine=Deadline|first1=Lisa|last1=de Moraes|date=September 14, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> In the lead-up to the show's taping, Oz promoted Trump's appearance with a claim that Oz would assess medical records submitted to the show by Trump and reveal his assessment on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/dr-oz-trump-medical-records-228089#ixzz4KFueVKZq|title=Dr. Oz pledges to avoid questions Trump 'doesn't want to have answered'|publisher=Politico|first1=Nick|last1=Gass|date=September 9, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Several news outlets speculated that Trump's appearance aimed to appeal to ''The Dr. Oz Show's'' large female viewership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/09/16/opinions/trump-clinton-health-war-vox-opinion/index.html|title=Trump and Oz: A match made in tv heaven|publisher=CNN|first1=Ford|last1=Vox|date=September 18, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/09/14/media/dr-oz-donald-trump-taping/index.html|title=Donald Trump surprises Dr. Oz with results of recent physical|publisher=CNN|first1=Brian|last1=Stetler|first2=MJ|last2=Lee|date=September 14, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Trump appointed Oz, athletes and ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' star [[Lou Ferrigno]] to his Council on Sports, Fitness, and Nutrition. Trump's selections were criticized as choosing \"pundits over experts\" for the panel.<ref name=intelligencer>{{Cite web |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/05/trump-appoints-incredible-hulk-and-dr-oz-to-sports-panel.html |title=Trump Appoints Incredible Hulk, Athletes, and Dr. Oz to Sports Panel |last=Raymond |first=Adam K. |date=2018-05-04 |website=Intelligencer |language=en |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n===Lack of scientific validity===\n[[File:McCaskill Takes Aim at Diet Scams That Are 'A Crisis in Consumer Protection'.webm|thumb|right|Oz was heavily criticised by Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] in a hearing on consumer fraud in diet product advertising.]]\n''[[Popular Science]]''<ref name=\"PopSci\">{{cite web |url=http://www.popsci.com/science/article/2013-01/dr-oz-bad-science |title=Is Dr. Oz Bad For Science? |work=[[Popular Science]] |date=January 30, 2013 |access-date=March 11, 2014 |author=Lecher, Colin}}</ref> and ''[[The New Yorker]]''<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2013/02/04/130204fa_fact_specter |title=The Operator |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=February 4, 2013 |access-date=March 11, 2014 |author=Specter, Michael|author-link=Michael Specter}}</ref> have published critical articles on Oz for giving \"non-scientific\" advice and questioning if he is \"doing more harm than good\"<ref name=\"NewYorker\" />\n\nThe [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] has awarded Oz with their [[Pigasus Award]], an award intended \"to expose parapsychological, paranormal or psychic frauds that Randi has noted over the previous year.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/component/content/article/37-static/256-pigasus-awards.html |title=Pigasus Awards |first=Jeff |last=Wagg |publisher=James Randi Educational Foundation |date=October 31, 2008 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2009, Oz received the award for the promotion of energy therapies such as [[Reiki]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pigasus Awards |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/swift-blog/928-the-2009-pigasus-awards.html |publisher=James Randi Education Foundation |date=April 2, 2010 |access-date= October 14, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Oz received the award for support of [[faith healing]] and [[mediumship|psychic communication with the dead]], among other controversial practices. Oz became the first person to receive a Pigasus Award two years in a row.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/health/boostershots/la-heb-dr-oz-andrew-wakefield-james-randi-awards-20110401,0,3573991.story |title=Dr. Oz, Andrew Wakefield and others, um, 'honored' by James Randi |access-date=April 2, 2011 |author=Mestel, Rosie |date=April 1, 2011 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In 2012, Oz won \"The Pigasus Award for Refusal to Face Reality\" for his continued promotion of \"quack medical practices, paranormal belief, and pseudoscience\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Randi|first1=James|authorlink=James Randi|title=JREF's Pigasus Awards \"Honors\" Dubious Peddlers of \"Woo\" |url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/jref-news/2074-jrefs-pigasus-awards-honors-dubious-peddlers-of-woo.html |publisher=James Randi Education Foundation |date=April 1, 2013 |access-date= October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 study published in the ''British Medical Journal'' found that medical talk shows such as ''The Dr Oz Show'' and ''The Doctors'' often lack adequate information on the specific benefits or evidence of their claims. 40 episodes of each program from early 2013 were evaluated, determining that evidence supported 46 percent, contradicted 15 percent and was not found for 39 percent of the recommendations on ''The Dr Oz Show''.<ref name=fast/><ref name=\"mehmetpost\">{{cite journal|last1=Korownyk |first1=Christina |title=Televised medical talk shows\u2014what they recommend and the evidence to support their recommendations: a prospective observational study |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g7346 |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=349 |pages=g7346 |doi=10.1136/bmj.g7346 |pmid=25520234 |date= December 17, 2014|pmc=4269523}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, a group of ten physicians from prestigious institutions called for Columbia University to part ways with Oz, who was the vice chair of the Department of Surgery. More than 1,300 doctors signed a letter sent to the university.<ref name=fast/><ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2015/04/17/health/dr-oz-columbia-letter/ \"Physicians to Columbia University: 'Dismayed' that Dr. Oz is on faculty\"]. [[CNN]]. April 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Viewpoints==\n===Medical marijuana===\nOz denounced the \"hypocrisy\" in the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]]'s classification of [[cannabis]] as a Schedule I, controlled substance on ''[[Fox & Friends]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.leafly.com/news/podcasts/podcast-the-roll-up-3-dr-oz-and-fox-friends |title=The Roll-Up #3: Dr. Oz and Fox & Friends |date=2017-09-22 |website=Leafly |language=en-US |access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> He has advocated for medical marijuana as a solution for the [[opioid epidemic]] during an episode of the series featuring [[Montel Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefix.com/dr-oz-and-montel-williams-whether-marijuana-can-treat-opioid-addiction |title=Dr. Oz and Montel Williams on Whether Marijuana Can Treat Opioid Addiction |date=2017-09-22 |website=The Fix |language=en |access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n===Backpage===\nOz has voiced his support of shutting down [[Backpage]], a controversial website which was seized by U.S. authorities in April 2018. Backpage has earned millions of dollars by allowing sex ads to be hosted on its website, some of which featured children. The site has been supported by the [[Center for Democracy and Technology]] and the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/opinion/outlook/article/Mazzio-Oz-Kids-are-no-match-for-Backpage-11107837.php|title=Mazzio, Oz: Kids are no match for 'Backpage'|last1=Mazzio|first1=Mary|last2=Oz|first2=Mehmet|date=April 28, 2017|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/siriusxmentertainment/dr-oz-shutting-down-backpagecom|title=Dr. Oz: Shutting Down Backpage|last1=Oz|first1=Mehmet|publisher=SiriusXM Entertainment|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> The [[Stop Enabling Sex Traffickers Act]] (SESTA) and the Allow States and Victims to Fight Online Sex Trafficking Act (FOSTA) have been passed by the [[U.S. Congress]] in 2018 as a response to Backpage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/01/10/backpage-com-shuts-down-adult-services-ads-after-relentless-pressure-from-authorities|title=Backpage.com shuts down adult services ads after relentless pressure from authorities|last1=Hawkins|first1=Derek|date=January 10, 2017|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Lisa Oz Mehmet Oz David Shankbone 2010.jpg|thumb|Oz and his wife Lisa]]\nOz lives in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey|Cliffside Park]], [[New Jersey]], with his wife [[Lisa Oz|Lisa]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Bruni, Frank | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/18/magazine/18Oz-t.html |title=Dr. Does-It-All |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 16, 2010 |access-date=March 22, 2011 |quote=That is his base line, to which he adds more yoga, short runs and basketball games with friends near his home in Cliffside Park, N.J., when he can.| author-link=Frank Bruni }}</ref> They have been married since 1985<ref>Married on July 29, 1985 in Bryn Athyn, PA \u2013 ''New Church Life'', 1985, p. 430.</ref> and have four children and four grandchildren.<ref>[https://people.com/parents/daphne-oz-welcomes-daughter-giovanna-ines-exclusive/ (August 15, 2019). Baby Makes Six! Daphne Oz Welcomes Daughter Giovanna Ines. People Magazine.]</ref> His eldest daughter is author and television host [[Daphne Oz]]. Oz and his wife founded [[HealthCorps]], a [[non-profit organization]] for [[health]] [[education]] and [[peer mentoring]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.success.com/how-dr-oz-healthcorps-is-creating-young-leaders/ |title=How Dr. Oz's HealthCorps Is Creating Young Leaders |date=2018-10-05 |website=SUCCESS |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nOz is fluent in English and [[Turkish Language|Turkish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkturkey.us/2009/07/the-wizard-of-dr-oz.html |title=The Wizard of Dr Oz \u2013 talkturkey |publisher=Talkturkey.us |date= July 19, 2009 |access-date= May 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520011523/http://www.talkturkey.us/2009/07/the-wizard-of-dr-oz.html |archive-date=May 20, 2010 }}</ref> He is a holder of [[Turkish nationality law|Turkish]] and American citizenship, having served in the [[Turkish Army]] to retain his Turkish citizenship.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/30/magazine/the-experiments-of-dr-oz.html?pagewanted=3 | work= [[The New York Times]] | title=The Experiments of Dr. Oz | first=Chip | last=Brown | date= July 30, 1995 | access-date= May 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOz grew up in a mixed [[Muslim]] environment where his father's family practiced more traditional [[Islam]], while his mother's family were more [[secular]] Muslims.<ref>{{cite video |people=Dr. Oz |year= 2010|title=Islam and Identity |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/video/islam-and-identity/140/ |format=Flash Video |medium= |trans_title= |publisher=PBS |location= |access-date= April 22, 2010}}</ref> Oz identifies himself as a Muslim<ref name=\"Business Insider\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/these-9-famous-americans-are-all-muslim-2014-10|title=9 Famous Americans You Probably Didn't Know Were Muslim |publisher=businessinsider.com |date= October 27, 2014 |access-date= April 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"wfaa8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/health/2014/08/10/13618098/ |title=Dr. Oz: The inside story |publisher=[[WFAA|WFAA.com]] |date=August 10, 2014 |access-date=April 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120093330/http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/health/2014/08/10/13618098/ |archive-date=January 20, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and says that he has been influenced by the mysticism of [[Sufi]] Muslims from Central Turkey,<ref name=\"theroot1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theroot.com/multimedia/meet-faces-america-dr-mehmet-oz |title=Henry Louis Gates Jr. Faces of America: Dr. Mehmet Oz |publisher=Theroot.com |date=August 19, 2010 |access-date=August 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424075849/http://www.theroot.com/multimedia/meet-faces-america-dr-mehmet-oz |archive-date=April 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as the ideas of [[Emanuel Swedenborg]], the 18th-century Swedish theologian, scientist, philosopher, revelator and mystic.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Martin Gardner |last=Gardner |first=Martin |year=2010 |title=Swedenborg and Dr. Oz. |journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |volume=34 |number=5 |url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/swedenborg_and_dr._oz/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spirituality-health.com/NMagazine/articles.php?id=1768 |title=Spirituality & Health: Mehmet Oz Finds His Teacher |publisher=Spirituality-health.com |date= |access-date= May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOz is a practitioner of [[Transcendental Meditation technique|transcendental meditation]]. \"When I meditate, I go to that place where truth lives,\" he said. \"I can see what reality really is, and it is so much easier to form good relationships then.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/features/tribu/ct-tribu-skube-multitasking,0,5213589.column | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Become a wizard of multitasking! | first=Daneen | last=Skube}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Oz was diagnosed with a pre-cancerous [[Polyp (medicine)|polyp]] in the colon during a routine [[colonoscopy]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2010/09/dr-oz-high-risk-after-cancer-scare/1 | work=USAToday.com | title=Dr. Oz 'high risk' after cancer scare | date= September 1, 2010 | access-date= October 18, 2010}}</ref> which was performed as part of his show. Oz said that the procedure likely saved his life.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20417551,00.html |work=People |title=Dr. Oz Has Colon Cancer Scare |first=Charlotte |last=Triggs |date= September 1, 2010| access-date= November 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Oz played for the \"Home\" roster during the [[2019 NBA All-Star Game#Celebrity Game|NBA All-Star Celebrity Game]] at the [[Bojangles' Coliseum]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]. The roster was made up of celebrities with Carolina roots.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/article/2019/02/06/2019-celebrity-game-participants-official-release |title=ESPN and NBA announce celebrity rosters and coaches for 2019 NBA All-Star Celebrity Game presented by Ruffles exclusively on ESPN |last=release |first=Official |website=NBA.com |language=en |access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> He previously played in the [[2010 NBA All-Star Game#Celebrity Game|NBA All-Star Celebrity Game]].<ref name=\"charlotte\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.valdostadailytimes.com/news/lifestyles/he-ll-be-the-oldest-player-in-the-nba-all/article_5b6c62ab-fce7-5a1b-9234-cdc8b804a1a5.html |title=He'll be the oldest player in the NBA All-Star Celebrity Game. Why is Dr. Oz doing this? |last=Janes |first=Th\u00e9oden   |website=The Charlotte Observer |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Also in 2019, Oz played for Team Cleveland in [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[All-Star Legends & Celebrity Softball Game]] at [[Progressive Field]] in Cleveland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Dan |title=MLB All-Star celebrity softball game 2019: Roster boasts famous names, former athletes, J.R. Smith |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/mlb-celebrity-softball-game-2019-full-roster-boasts-famous-names-former-athletes-jr-smith/86olgiinxyhz1rhb1ji30yupe |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=July 8, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999-2004, Oz was named a \"Global Leader of Tomorrow\" by the [[World Economic Forum]]<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wnet/facesofamerica/profiles/dr-mehmet-oz/4/</ref> and was listed on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine's]]'' \"100 Most Influential People\" of 2008.<ref>http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1733748_1733754_1735329,00.html</ref> He has been nominated for nine [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host|Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Talk Show Host]] since ''The Dr. Oz Show'' premiered in 2009, and won the award in 2010, 2011, 2014 and 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2016/05/02/General-Hospital-Live-with-Kelly-Michael-win-big-at-the-Daytime-Emmy-Awards/2271462123287/|date=May 2, 2016|title='General Hospital,' 'Live with Kelly & Michael' win big at the Daytime Emmy Awards|author=Butler, Karen| publisher = [[United Press International]] |access-date=May 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2014/06/22/daytime-emmys-2014-winners/ |title=Daytime Emmys: Y&R Dominates Soap Pack; AMC and OLTL Get 3 Wins Each |last=Mitovich |first=Matt Webb |last2=Mitovich |first2=Matt Webb |date=2014-06-23 |website=TVLine |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2011/06/2011-daytime-emmy-award-winners-141381/ |title=2011 Daytime Emmy Award Winners |last=Team |first=The Deadline |last2=Team |first2=The Deadline |date=2011-06-20 |website=Deadline |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2010/06/2010-daytime-emmy-winners-as-the-world-turns-bold-beautiful-cash-cab-and-dr-oz-49888/ |title=2010 Daytime Emmy Winners: 'As The World Turns', 'Bold & Beautiful', 'Young & Restless', 'General Hospital', 'Cash Cab', 'Ellen', 'Dr Oz', And 'The Doctors' |last=Finke |first=Nikki |last2=Finke |first2=Nikki |date=2010-06-28 |website=Deadline |language=en |access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Medical journalism]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last=Brown |first=Heidi |url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/08/04/oprah-health-doctor-forbeslife-cx_hb_0804oz.html |title=Oprah Loves This Doctor |journal=[[Forbes|Forbes Magazine]] |date=August 4, 2008 |access-date=June 1, 2015}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Specter |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Specter |date=February 4, 2013 |title=The operator : is the most trusted doctor in America doing more harm than good? |department=Profiles |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=88 |issue=46 |pages=40\u201349 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/02/04/the-operator |access-date=January 9, 2015}}\n* {{Cite news |last=Gladstone |first=Brooke |author-link=Brooke Gladstone |title=Dr. Oz Fights for Credibility |url=http://www.onthemedia.org/story/dr-oz-fights-credibility/ |work=[[On the Media]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=April 24, 2015 |access-date=June 1, 2015}} Discussion with Michael Specter about his profile of Oz.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mehmet Oz}}\n* [http://columbiasurgery.org/mehmet-c-oz-md-facs Columbia University Department of Surgery profile]\n* {{IMD