ck Eyed Peas |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Elephunk-Explicit-Lyrics-Black-Eyed/dp/B0000ATU53 |title=Elephunk [Explicit Lyrics&#93;: Amazon.co.uk: Music |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-08-10}}</ref>\n| August 7, 2003\n| [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Elephunk-Black-Eyed-Peas/dp/B00029LNHS |title=Elephunk: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-10}}</ref>\n| May 26, 2004\n| Re-issue\n| A&M\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n{{The Black Eyed Peas}}\n\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:The Black Eyed Peas albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ron Fair]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by will.i.am]]\n[[Category:Interscope Geffen A&M Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Elefunk}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Elephunk\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Black Eyed Peas]]\n| cover      = Elephunk.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 24, 2003\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]<ref name=\"Sawyer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/blackeyedpeas-elephunk/|title=Black Eyed Peas: Elephunk|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|last=Sawyer|first=Terry|date=July 17, 2003|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> \n*[[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=Christgau/>\n| length     = 59:29\n| label      = \n*[[A&M Records|A&M]]\n*[[will.i.am Music Group|will.i.am]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[apl.de.ap]]\n*[[Ron Fair]]\n*Poet Named Life\n*[[will.i.am]] }}\n| prev_title = [[Bridging the Gap (Black Eyed Peas album)|Bridging the Gap]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Monkey Business (The Black Eyed Peas album)|Monkey Business]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Elephunk\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Where Is the Love?]]\n | single1date = June 16, 2003\n | single2     = [[Shut Up (The Black Eyed Peas song)|Shut Up]]\n | single2date = November 4, 2003\n | single3     = [[Hey Mama (The Black Eyed Peas song)|Hey Mama]]\n | single3date = January 12, 2004\n | single4     = [[Let's Get It Started]]\n | single4date = June 22, 2004\n}}\n}}\n'''''Elephunk''''' is the third [[studio album]] by American group [[The Black Eyed Peas]]. It was released on June 24, 2003, by the [[will.i.am Music Group]] and [[A&M Records]]. The album charted at number 14 on the American [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart and was certified double platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], and has gone on to sell more than 9&nbsp;million copies worldwide, with 3.2&nbsp;million in the United States alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/65105/week-ending-aug-29-2010-lifes-upsdowns/;_ylt=As.ddN4VLBr5p7c35m1V7J0PwiUv?page=2#comments |title=Week Ending Aug. 29, 2010: Life's Ups & Downs \u2013 Chart Watch |publisher=New.music.yahoo.com |date=September 1, 2010 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref> This is the group's first album with [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], as well as their first album where the band is credited as ''The'' Black Eyed Peas. Album cover art by Markus and [[Indrani Pal-Chaudhuri]]).\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 66/100<ref name=meta>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/elephunk/the-black-eyed-peas |title=Reviews for Elephunk by The Black Eyed Peas |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/elephunk-mw0000035954 |title=Elephunk \u2013 The Black Eyed Peas |last=Bush |first=John |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2Score = 4/5<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Black Eyed Peas: Elephunk |work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=182 |date=September 2003 |page=118}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.blender.com:80/reviews/review_1701.html |title=The Black Eyed Peas: Elephunk |last=Patel |first=Joseph |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=18 |date=August 2003 |accessdate=June 2, 2017 |page=120 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040820014052/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_1701.html |archivedate=August 20, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| rev4Score = 9/10<ref name=DiS/>\n| rev5 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev5Score = C<ref name=EW>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,459854,00.html |title=Elephunk |last=Serpick |first=Evan |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 27, 2003 |accessdate=May 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142040/https://ew.com/article/2003/06/27/elephunk/ |archivedate=November 29, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev6Score = 4.0/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.297/title.black-eyed-peas-elephunk |title=Black Eyed Peas \u2013 Elephunk |last=Tindal |first=K. B. |work=[[HipHopDX]] |date=July 24, 2003 |accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/elephunk-20030618 |title=Elephunk |last=Hardy |first=Ernest |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=June 18, 2003 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/black-eyed-peas/albumguide |title=Black Eyed Peas: Album Guide |last=Weingarten |first=Christopher R. |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=June 2, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424105307/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/black-eyed-peas/albumguide |archivedate=April 24, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = B+<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gxaz3RhzGKoC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119 |title=Breakdown |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=19 |issue=8 |date=August 2003 |accessdate=June 2, 2017 |page=119}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=Christgau>{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-01-27/music/parts-of-the-elephunk/1 |title=Parts of the Elephunk |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=January 27, 2004 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Normalization (statistics)|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has received an average score of 66, based on 15 reviews indicating generally positive reviews.<ref name=meta/> John Bush from [[AllMusic]] said that ''Elephunk'' \"possesses some of the most boundary-pushing productions in contemporary, (mostly) uncommercial [[hip hop music|hip-hop]]\".<ref name=Allmusic/><ref>{{cite web |title=Elephunk - Black Eyed Peas |url=http://www.billboard.com/album/the-black-eyed-peas/elephunk/588226#/album/black-eyed-peas/elephunk/588226/review |work=Billboard }}</ref> Chris Nettleton from ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'' complimented the album, saying: \"This record is full of first rate rapping, first rate tunes, first rate instrumentation. Look on the surface, and you've got an album full of memorable songs, hooks that lodge in your mind... but look in depth, and it's quality from the top down.\"<ref name=DiS>{{cite web |title=Album Review: Black Eyed Peas \u2013 Elephunk |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/3683/reviews/9600- |last=Nettleton |first=Chris |work=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=May 10, 2004 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref> In his consumer guide for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] commented that the group \"remain unbelievable, but in [[pop music|pop]] that's just one more aesthetic nuance\", and stated, \"In which the unbelievably dull El Lay alt-rappers fabricate the brightest actual rap album of 2003.\"<ref name=Christgau/>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' had more of a negative view on the record: \"They try [[dancehall]] ('[[Hey Mama (The Black Eyed Peas song)|Hey Mama]]'), [[salsa music|salsa]] ('Latin Girls'), even [[nu metal|nu-metal]] ('Anxiety' with [[Papa Roach]]), but the biggest offense for a once smart-sounding rap collective is '[[Where Is the Love?]]', the horrifyingly trite single. It's enough to make longtime fans wonder, 'Where are the Peas?'\".<ref name=EW/>\n\n==Commercial response==\nIn the United States, ''Elephunk'' reached number 14 on the ''[[Billboard Top 200]]'' and was their first album to chart in the top 15. On the [[UK Album Charts]] it reached number 3. It has sold over 1.6&nbsp;million copies in the UK and 8.5&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amazon Elephunk Information |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00009V7RF}}</ref>\n\nThe band was approached by EA games to feature some of their music on the 2004 game ''[[The Urbz: Sims in the City|The Urbz]]''. They remixed some of the tracks on ''Elephunk'' and translated it into [[Simlish]] and created new tracks for the game. They appear in the game as playable characters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Black Eyed Peas To Feature In The Urbz: Sims In The City |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6105705.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107052159/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6105705.html |archivedate=2012-11-07 }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Track listings ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n\n| title1          = Hands Up\n| writer1         = {{flat list|\n*[[will.i.am|Will Adams]]\n*[[apl.de.ap|Allan Pineda]]\n*[[Taboo (rapper)|Jaime Gomez]]\n*[[George Pajon]], Jr.\n*Michael Fratantuno\n*[[Jean Baptiste (record producer)|Jean Baptiste]]\n*Billy May\n}}\n| extra1          = [[will.i.am]]\n| length1         = 3:35\n\n| title2          = Labor Day (It's a Holiday)\n| wri