04|title=Rapports Annuels 2004|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|96\n|-\n|Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-2004|title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|language=German|work=GfK Entertainment|publisher=offiziellecharts.de|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|Hungary (R\u00e1di\u00f3s Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zene.slagerlistak.hu/archivum/eves-osszesitett-listak/radios/2004|title=R\u00e1di\u00f3s Top 100 - hallgatotts\u00e1gi adatok alapj\u00e1n - 2004|accessdate=3 April 2020|publisher=[[Mahasz]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|95\n|-\n|Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/2004|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 2004|publisher=Dutch Top 40|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|57\n|-\n|Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=2004&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 2004|website=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|75\n|-\n|Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/charts/jahreshitparade/2004|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 2004|website=hitparade.ch|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukchartsplus.co.uk/ChartsPlusYE2004.pdf|title=UK Year-End Chart 2004|format=PDF|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|79\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboardtop100of.com/2004-2/|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 2004|website=billboardtop100of.com|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|95\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|A0aYaX6j5hM|Music video for \"Hey Mama\"}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090426084129/http://www.younnta.com/2009/04/23/black-eyed-peas-hey-mama-lyrics-music-video/ Hey Mama (lyrics , video)]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|black-eyed-peas|hey-mama}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Black Eyed Peas}}\n\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:2006 singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by will.i.am]]\n[[Category:Songs written by will.i.am]]\n[[Category:The Black Eyed Peas songs]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Fatima Robinson]]\n", "name_user": "31.0.34.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hey_Mama_(The_Black_Eyed_Peas_song)"}
{"title_page": "Maria de Sousa", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Portuguese immunologist and poet}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maria de Sousa\n| honorific-suffix = [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GCSE]] [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GOSE]] [[Order of Prince Henry|GOIH]]\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Maria \u00c2ngela Brito de Sousa\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1939|10|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2020|4|14|1939|10|17|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Arroios (Lisbon)|Arroios]], [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| death_cause   = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Immunologist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Maria de Sousa''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GCSE]] [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GOSE]] [[Order of Prince Henry|GOIH]]}} (17 October 1939 \u2013 14 April 2020) was a Portuguese [[immunologist]], poet and writer. She gained international recognition as a medical researcher, as the author of several seminal scientific papers: she was the first to describe thymus-dependent (or [[T cell|T cell]]) areas in 1966, a fundamental discovery in the mapping of [[Lymphatic system|peripheral lymphoid organs]]; and coined the term \"ecotaxis\" in 1971, to describe the phenomenon of cells of different origins to migrate and to organize among themselves in very specific lymphoid areas.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Duarte |first1=Delfim |date= |title=Ever-changing homes |url=https://journals.lww.com/pbj/Fulltext/2019/04000/Ever_changing_homes.5.aspx |journal=Porto Biomedical Journal |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=e33 |doi=10.1016/j.pbj.0000000000000033 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Later, in the 1980s she focused on the study of [[hereditary hemochromatosis]], an iron overload genetic disease.<ref name=\"i3S\">{{cite web |url=https://www.i3s.up.pt/news?v=97 |title=Professor Maria de Sousa passed away |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=Instituto de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o e Inova\u00e7\u00e3o em Sa\u00fade (i3S), University of Porto |access-date=16 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nMaria de Sousa died in Lisbon on 14 April 2020, a victim of that year's [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portugal|coronavirus pandemic]], after a week in the [[intensive care unit]] of [[Hospital de S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9|S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Hospital]].<ref name=\"i3S\"/> Among the many top figures in Portuguese science and society that paid homage to Sousa, the [[President of Portugal|President of the Republic]], [[Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa]], issued a statement offering his condolences to the family, referring to her as a \"unmatched figure in Portuguese science\" and underscoring her \"inescapable legacy in science and great example in rigor, exigence, and civic and cultural commitment\".<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=\"Uma cientista de corpo inteiro\" que fazia \"grandes perguntas\": as reac\u00e7\u00f5es \u00e0 morte de Maria de Sousa |trans-title=\"A full-body scientist\" who asked \"big questions\": reactions to Maria de Sousa's death |url=https://www.publico.pt/2020/04/14/ciencia/noticia/reaccoes-morte-maria-sousa-1912214 |language=Portuguese |work=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] |location= |access-date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Distinctions==\n===National orders===\n*[[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Officer BAR.svg|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Order of Prince Henry]] (9 June 1995)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\">{{cite web|title=Cidad\u00e3os Nacionais Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153&list=1|website=P\u00e1gina Oficial das Ordens Honor\u00edficas Portuguesas|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Officer BAR.png|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|Order of Saint James of the Sword]] (20 January 2012)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n*[[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Cross BAR.png|80px]] Grand Cross of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|Order of Saint James of the Sword]] (18 November 2016)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* Parrott, DMV, de Sousa, MAB, and East, J. \"Thymus dependent areas in the lymphoid organs of neonatally thymectomized mice\". ''J. Exp. Med.''; l23: 191-1966.\n* Parrott, DMV and De Sousa, MAB. \"Changes in thymus-dependent areas of lymph nodes after immunological stimulation\". ''Nature'', 212: 1316-,1966.\n* De Sousa, MAB, Parrott, DMV and Pantelouris. \"Lymphoid tissues in mice with congenital aplasia of the thymus\". ''Clin.exp.Immunol.'' 4: 637-,1969.\n* Sousa, MD \"Kinetics of distribution of thymus and marrow cells in peripheral organs of the mouse \u2013 Ecotaxis\". ''Clin.exp.Immunol.'' 9: 371-,1971.\n* Broxmeyer, HE, Smithyman, A, Eger, RR, Meyer, PA and De Sousa, M. \"Identification of Lactoferrin as granulocyte derived inhibitor of colony stimulating activity production\". ''J. Exp. Med.'' 148: 1052-1067, 1977.\n* D\u00f6rner, M., Silverstone, A., Nishyia, K.,de Sostoa, A.,Munn, G and De Sousa, M. \"Ferritin synthesis by Human T lymphocytes\". ''Science'', 209: 1019-1021.\n* De Sousa M., Reim\u00e3o, R., Lacerda, R., Hugo, P. and Kaufman. S. \"Iron overload in \u00df2 microglobulin deficient mice\". ''Immunol. Lett.'' 39: 105-111. 1994.\n* Santos, M., Schilham, MW, Rademakers, LHPM, Marx, JJM, de Sousa, M. and Clevers, H. \"Defective iron homeostasis in beta 2-microglobulin knockout mice recapitulates Hereditary Hemochromatosis in man\". ''J.Exp.Med,'' 184: 1975-1985. 1996.\n* De Almeida SF, Carvalho IF, Cardoso CS, Cordeiro JV, Azevedo JE, Neefjes J, De Sousa M. (2005) \"HFE crosstalks with the MHC class I antigen presentation pathway\". ''Blood'' 106:971-7.\n* De Sousa, M. 2011. \"An outsider's perspective-ecotaxis revisited: an integrative review of cancer environment, iron and immune system cells\". ''Integr. Biol.'', 3, 343-349.\n* Hoshino A, Costa-Silva B, Shen TL, et al (2015). \"Tumour exosome integrins determine organotropic metastasis\". ''Nature'' 527(7578):329-35. Epub 2015 Oct 28.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sousa, Maria de}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Portuguese physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Portuguese physicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint James of the Sword]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the Order of Prince Henry]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the Order of Saint James of the Sword]]\n[[Category:Portuguese immunologists]]\n[[Category:Portuguese medical researchers]]\n[[Category:University of Lisbon alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Porto faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Portuguese immunologist and poet}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maria de Sousa\n| honorific-suffix = [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GCSE]] [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GOSE]] [[Order of Prince Henry|GOIH]]\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Maria \u00c2ngela Brito de Sousa\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1939|10|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2020|4|14|1939|10|17|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Arroios (Lisbon)|Arroios]], [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| death_cause   = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Immunologist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Maria de Sousa''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GCSE]] [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|GOSE]] [[Order of Prince Henry|GOIH]]}} (17 October 1939 \u2013 14 April 2020) was a Portuguese [[immunologist]], poet and writer. She gained international recognition as a medical researcher, as the author of several seminal scientific papers: she was the first to describe thymus-dependent (or [[T cell|T cell]]) areas in 1966, a fundamental discovery in the mapping of [[Lymphatic system|peripheral lymphoid organs]]; and coined the term \"ecotaxis\" in 1971, to describe the phenomenon of cells of different origins to migrate and to organize among themselves in very specific lymphoid areas.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Duarte |first1=Delfim |date= |title=Ever-changing homes |url=https://journals.lww.com/pbj/Fulltext/2019/04000/Ever_changing_homes.5.aspx |journal=Porto Biomedical Journal |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=e33 |doi=10.1016/j.pbj.0000000000000033 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Later, in the 1980s she focused on the study of [[hereditary hemochromatosis]], an iron overload genetic disease.<ref name=\"i3S\">{{cite web |url=https://www.i3s.up.pt/news?v=97 |title=Professor Maria de Sousa passed away |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=Instituto de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o e Inova\u00e7\u00e3o em Sa\u00fade (i3S), University of Porto |access-date=16 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nMaria de Sousa died in Lisbon on 14 April 2020, a victim of that year's [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portugal|coronavirus pandemic]], after a week in the [[intensive care unit]] of [[Hospital de S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9|S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Hospital]].<ref name=\"i3S\"/> Among the many top figures in Portuguese science and society that paid homage to Sousa, the [[President of Portugal|President of the Republic]], [[Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa]], issued a statement offering his condolences to the family, referring to her as a \"unmatched figure in Portuguese science\" and underscoring her \"inescapable legacy in science and great example in rigor, exigence, and civic and cultural commitment\".<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=\"Uma cientista de corpo inteiro\" que fazia \"grandes perguntas\": as reac\u00e7\u00f5es \u00e0 morte de Maria de Sousa |trans-title=\"A full-body scientist\" who asked \"big questions\": reactions to Maria de Sousa's death |url=https://www.publico.pt/2020/04/14/ciencia/noticia/reaccoes-morte-maria-sousa-1912214 |language=Portuguese |work=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] |location= |access-date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Distinctions==\n===National orders===\n*[[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Officer BAR.svg|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Order of Prince Henry]] (9 June 1995)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\">{{cite web|title=Cidad\u00e3os Nacionais Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153&list=1|website=P\u00e1gina Oficial das Ordens Honor\u00edficas Portuguesas|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Officer BAR.png|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|Order of Saint James of the Sword]] (20 January 2012)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n*[[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Cross BAR.png|80px]] Grand Cross of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword|Order of Saint James of the Sword]] (18 November 2016)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* Parrott, DMV, de Sousa, MAB, and East, J. \"Thymus dependent areas in the lymphoid organs of neonatally thymectomized mice\". ''J. Exp. Med.''; l23: 191-1966.\n* Parrott, DMV and De Sousa, MAB. \"Changes in thymus-dependent areas of lymph nodes after immunological stimulation\". ''Nature'', 212: 1316-,1966.\n* De Sousa, MAB, Parrott, DMV and Pantelouris. \"Lymphoid tissues in mice with congenital aplasia of the thymus\". ''Clin.exp.Immunol.'' 4: 637-,1969.\n* Sousa, MD \"Kinetics of distribution of thymus and marrow cells in peripheral organs of the mouse \u2013 Ecotaxis\